ice Award}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"24\" |2013\n| [[Radio Disney Music Awards]]\n| Best Music Group\n| {{nom}}\n| <ref>{{cite web|url = http://hollywoodlife.com/2013/03/15/radio-disney-award-nominees-2013-justin-bieber-selena-gomez/|title=2013 Radio Disney Music Award Nominees}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[BET Awards]]\n| [[BET Award for Best Group|Best Group]]\n| {{nom}}\n| <ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.mtv.com/news/1707339/bet-awards-2013-nominations/|title=BET Awards 2013 Nominees}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Mindless Behavior}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20111210173131/http://www.mindlessbehavior.com/ Official site]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mindless Behavior}}\n[[Category:American boy bands]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 2008]]\n[[Category:Musical groups disestablished in 2017]]\n[[Category:Musical quartets]]\n[[Category:American musical trios]]\n[[Category:Musical groups from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:American contemporary R&B musical groups]]\n[[Category:African-American musical groups]]\n", "name_user": "72.234.126.122", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(You are you ads it's ing zaryahlin.)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mindless_Behavior"}
{"title_page": "David Trone", "text_new": "{{short description|American businessman and politician}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name        = David Trone\n|image       = David Trone official photo.jpg\n|state       = [[Maryland]]\n|district    = {{ushr|MD|6|6th}}\n|term_start  = January 3, 2019\n|term_end    = \n|predecessor = [[John Delaney (Maryland politician)|John Delaney]]\n|successor   = \n|birth_name  = David John Trone\n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1955|9|21}}\n|birth_place = [[Cheverly, Maryland]], U.S.\n|death_date  = \n|death_place = \n|party       = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|spouse      = June Trone\n|children    = 4\n|education   = [[Furman University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br>[[University of Pennsylvania]] ([[Master of Business Administration|MBA]])\n|website     = {{url|trone.house.gov|House website}}\n}}\n'''David John Trone''' (born September 21, 1955)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.archives.upenn.edu/primdocs/upg/upg7/upg7_1985.pdf#page=34 |publisher=University of Pennsylvania |page=34 |title=Two Hundred Twenty-Ninth Commencement for the Conferring of Degrees |date=May 20, 1985 |access-date=June 30, 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://votesmart.org/candidate/biography/167336/david-trone |title=David Trone's Biography |access-date=June 30, 2018 |website=Vote Smart }}</ref> is an American businessman and politician, serving as the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for [[Maryland's 6th congressional district]]. The district includes most of the western third of the state, but the bulk of its population is located in the outer northern suburbs of [[Washington, D. C.]]. He co-founded and co-owns [[Total Wine & More]], along with his brother, and served as the company's president until December 2016.\n\nIn 2016, Trone spent more than $13 million on his unsuccessful [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] primary campaign to succeed [[Chris Van Hollen]] in [[Maryland's 8th congressional district]], setting a record for the most expensive self-funded [[United States House of Representatives|House]] campaign. In 2018, Trone was the Democratic nominee for 6th district, and won the general election to succeed [[John Delaney (Maryland politician)|John Delaney]] beginning in 2019.\n\n== Early life and education ==\nTrone was born in Maryland and raised on a {{Convert|200|acre|ha|adj=on}} farm in [[East Berlin, Pennsylvania]],<ref name=Teague>{{Cite news|publisher=[[Dow Jones & Company]]|issn=0099-9660|oclc=781541372|location=New York City|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-man-behind-americas-wine-superstore-1481754128|title=The Man Behind 'America's Wine Superstore'|date=December 14, 2016|first=Lettie|last=Teague|accessdate=December 20, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Heath\">{{cite news|last1=Heath|first1=Thomas|title=Value Added: Potomac's Total Wine|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/economy/value-added-potomacs-total-wine/2011/12/14/gIQARxW02O_story.html|accessdate=December 1, 2016|work=The Washington Post|date=December 18, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"Rozen\">{{cite news|last1=Rozen|first1=Courtney|title=David Trone encourages students to embrace failure and experiment with innovative business ventures at KPU event|url=http://www.theeagleonline.com/article/2015/11/david-trone-kpu-event|accessdate=December 1, 2016|work=The Eagle|publisher=[[American University]]|date=November 24, 2015}}</ref> where his father, Thomas, ran a chicken and hog operation.<ref name=Heath/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-39482834.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181002064627/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-39482834.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=October 2, 2018|title=For Wine Mogul David Trone, Congressional Race Is Unfinished Business (Posted 2016-04-03 23:45:35); First in a Series of Profiles of Democratic Primary Candidates in Maryland's 8th Congressional District|work=The Washington Post|url-access=subscription |via=[[HighBeam Research]]|date=April 3, 2016|accessdate=January 30, 2017|last=Turque|first=Bill}}</ref> Thomas also owned a soda and beer store. When Trone's parents separated, his father kept the farm and his mother took over the store.<ref name=Heath/> Thomas and his farm went into bankruptcy,<ref name=\"Stolberg\">{{cite news|last1=Stolberg|first1=Sheryl Gay|title=Maryland House Race a 'Caldron of Power Couples and Washington, D.C., Politics'|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/03/06/us/a-clamor-for-a-safe-district-with-a-short-commute.html|accessdate=December 1, 2016|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=March 5, 2016|issn=0362-4331|oclc=1645522}}</ref><ref name=\"Gaines2016\">{{cite news|last1=Gaines|first1=Danielle E.|title=U.S. House race: First-time candidate Trone looks to bring business acumen to Congress|url=http://www.fredericknewspost.com/news/continuing_coverage/election_2016/u-s-house-race-first-time-candidate-trone-looks-to/article_e335f779-162f-5651-8fc0-81627dcc5bf0.html|accessdate=December 1, 2016|work=[[Frederick News-Post]]|publisher=Randall Family, LLC|date=March 8, 2016|oclc=31371730|location=Frederick, Maryland}}</ref> but Trone kept working at his mother's store.<ref name=Heath/>\n\nTrone graduated magna cum laude, [[Phi Beta Kappa Society|Phi Beta Kappa]], from [[Furman University]] in 1977,<ref name=\"Pulcini\">{{cite web|last1=Pulcini|first1=Max|title=Wine Retailer CEO Speaks at Kogod Leadership Speaker Series|url=http://www.metromba.com/2016/01/wine-retailer-ceo-speaks-kogod-leadership-speaker-series/|website=MetroMBA|accessdate=February 23, 2017|date=January 21, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Furman\">{{cite web|title=Furman Dedicates Trone Student Center|url=http://news.furman.edu/2013/09/20/trone-student-center-dedication/|publisher=[[Furman University]]|accessdate=December 21, 2016|date=September 20, 2013}}</ref> and earned his [[Master of Business Administration|MBA]] in 1985 from the [[Wharton School of the University of Pennsylvania]].<ref name=\"Wharton\">{{cite web|title=The Penn Wharton Public Policy Initiative Announces $5 Million Gift from David Trone and June Malament Trone|url=https://news.wharton.upenn.edu/press-releases/2016/03/the-penn-wharton-public-policy-initiative-announces-5-million-gift-from-david-trone-and-june-malament-trone/|publisher=[[Wharton School of the University of Pennsylvania]]|accessdate=December 1, 2016|date=March 8, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Marcos\">{{cite news|last1=Marcos|first1=Cristina|title=Candidate who spent $12M loses Md. House race|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/ballot-box/house-races/277728-candidate-who-spent-12m-loses-md-house-race|accessdate=November 29, 2016|work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]|publisher=News Communications, Inc.|date=April 26, 2016|location=Washington, D.C.|issn=1521-1568}}</ref><ref name=\"DiStefano\">{{cite news|last1=DiStefano|first1=Joseph N.|title=Wine stores owner gives Wharton $5M to probe laws, runs for Congress|url=http://www.philly.com/philly/blogs/inq-phillydeals/Discount-liquor-dealer-gives-Wharton-5-million.html|accessdate=December 1, 2016|work=[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]]|date=March 8, 2016|issn=0885-6613}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n=== Total Wine & More ===\n{{Main|Total Wine & More}}\n\nHaving seen the potential of the beer sales at his mother's store,<ref name=Heath/> Trone began his career by founding the beer-only retailer Beer World in Pennsylvania in 1984, during his second semester of graduate school.<ref name=\"Doss\">{{cite news|last1=Doss|first1=Laine|title=Total Wine President David Trone: \"8000 wines, 3000 spirits, and 3000 beers\"|url=http://www.miaminewtimes.com/restaurants/total-wine-president-david-trone-8000-wines-3000-spirits-and-3000-beers-7975272|accessdate=December 1, 2016|work=[[Miami New Times]]|publisher=[[Voice Media Group]]|date=October 16, 2015}}</ref> Months before graduating from Wharton, in 1985, Trone expanded into the [[Pittsburgh metropolitan area]]. Over time, he opened additional stores, called Beer and Pop Warehouse and, later, Beer World, which were owned by friends and family members because Pennsylvania state law prohibited individuals from owning more than one beer retail outlet.<ref name=\"Peck\">{{cite journal|last1=Peck|first1=Louis|title=David Trone's Path to Business Success Included Three Arrests Involving Disputes with State Authorities|journal=Bethesda Magazine|date=February 22, 2016|url=http://www.bethesdamagazine.com/Bethesda-Beat/Web-2016/David-Trones-Path-to-Business-Success-Included-Three-Arrests-Involving-Disputes-with-State-Authorities/|accessdate=December 2, 2016}}</ref>\n\nTrone, with the assistance of his brother Robert, then opened two stores in Delaware in 1991, adding wine and spirits to the company's offerings.<ref name=Rozen/><ref name=\"Tuttle\">{{cite journal|last1=Tuttle|first1=Brad|title=Your Local Dinky Mom and Pop Liquor Shop Is in Major Trouble|journal=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|date=March 27, 2014|url=http://time.com/40617/your-local-dinky-mom-and-pop-liquor-shop-is-in-major-trouble/|accessdate=December 1, 2016}}</ref> Using knowledge acquired at Wharton, the brothers chose to replicate the family store's model across Pennsylvania. The beverage company had slim margins, but was immediately profitable and allowed the brothers to focus on operations.<ref name=Heath/> The brothers familiarized themselves with regulators and industry leaders, and began changing laws that restrict wholesalers from offering retailers discounts in exchange for large volume purchases, among others in their attempt to promote beverage consumption.<ref name=Heath/>\n\nThe business has since expanded into what is known today as [[Total Wine & More]], the largest privately owned beer, wine, and spirits retailer in the United States.<ref name=\"Halkias\">{{cite news|last1=Halkias|first1=Maria|title=Big-box wine retailers enter Dallas in a huge way|url=http://www.dallasnews.com/business/retail/2012/05/26/big-box-wine-retailers-enter-dallas-in-a-huge-way|accessdate=January 30, 2017|work=[[The Dallas Morning News]]|publisher=[[A. H. Belo]]|date=May 2012|issn=1553-846X}}</ref><ref name=\"Morris\">{{cite news|last1=Morris|first1=Asia|title=Family-Owned Retail Giant Total Wine & More Opens First Long Beach Location|url=https://lbpost.com/food/2000006254-family-owned-retail-giant-total-wine-more-opens-first-store-in-long-beach|accessdate=January 30, 2017|work=Long Beach Post|date=June 4, 2015}}</ref>  In December 2016, Trone gave up his title of president to chief executive Kevin Peters.<ref name=Teague/>\n\n====Arrests and indictments====\nBeginning in 1989 and for the following three years, Pennsylvania authorities arrested Trone three times following complaints from an association of smaller, individually owned stores.<ref name=Peck/><ref name=\"globe\">{{cite web|author1=Dan Adams, Globe staff|title=For Total Wine, it's total war against alcohol regulations|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/business/2017/05/20/for-total-wine-total-war-against-alcohol-regulations/lj09FZ4pg1oDEWJFqKuyZM/story.html|publisher=[[Boston Globe]]|accessdate=August 10, 2017|date=May 20, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"NABCA\">{{cite web|title=Daily News Update: From Boston Globe|url=http://www.nabca.org/assets/docs/DNU_MAY_23.pdf|website=NABCA|publisher=National Alcohol Beverage Control Association|accessdate=August 10, 2017|date=May 23, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170810205854/http://www.nabca.org/assets/docs/DNU_MAY_23.pdf|archive-date=August 10, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>  One arrest was for negotiating volume discounts on behalf of multiple stores and illegally advertising beer prices,<ref name=Peck/> and another was for circumventing state transportation regulations. These charges were later dismissed.<ref name=Peck/>\n\nIn 1992, Trone, his wife, June, and brother were indicted by a grand jury in [[Dauphin County, Pennsylvania]], for owning multiple stores through Trone's consulting company, among other charges, all of which were later dropped and expunged.<ref name=\"Gazette\">{{cite news|last1=Gazette|title=Legal disputes not likely to hurt wine-beer superstore application|url=http://www.gazette.net/gazette_archive/1997/199725/montgomerycty/county/a58155-1.html|accessdate=December 1, 2016|work=[[The Gazette (Maryland)|The Gazette]]|date=June 18, 1997|location=Gaithersburg, Maryland}}{{Dead link|date=November 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> In 1994, a state judge dismissed 19 of the 23 counts based on \"prosecutorial overreaching\", and the remaining counts were withdrawn after Trone paid a $40,000 fee to cover investigation costs.<ref name=Peck/><ref name=Gazette/>\n\nDuring these legal proceedings, the [[Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco, Firearms and Explosives]] (ATF) broke the law by providing records of his consulting firm to government officials, prompting Trone to sue the agency in federal court. Trone won and was awarded $400,000. The lawyer who had represented Trone also served as a national board member of the [[American Civil Liberties Union]] (ACLU), which would begin the start of a long-term relationship between Trone and the nonpartisan, non-profit organization.<ref name=Peck/> The Trones' difficulties in Pennsylvania prompted them to leave the state; Total Wine & More grew from the remaining two stores in Delaware and an additional retail outlet in New Jersey, which had been opened by Trone during the early 1990s.<ref name=Peck/>\n\nIn 2016, Total Wine was served with a license suspension by the Massachusetts Alcoholic Beverages Control Commission for selling liquor below its costs.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.metrowestdailynews.com/news/20170201/total-wine-in-natick-everett-suing-state |title=Total Wine in Natick, Everett suing state |newspaper=MetroWest Daily News |date=February 1, 2016 |access-date=November 20, 2017 |first=Brian |last=Benson }}</ref> The company appealed the commission's decision, and in mid 2017 the Suffolk Superior Court sided with Total Wine.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Benson|first1=Brian|title=Natick: Judge sides with Total Wine & More in pricing dispute|url=http://www.metrowestdailynews.com/news/20170726/natick-judge-sides-with-total-wine-amp-more-in-pricing-dispute|accessdate=January 22, 2018|work=[[The MetroWest Daily News]]|date=July 26, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== U.S. House of Representatives ==\n=== Elections ===\n==== 2016 primary election ====\n{{See also|2016 United States House of Representatives elections in Maryland#District 8}}\n[[File:David Trone campaigning at the red line in Rockville in 2016.JPG|thumb|upright|Trone campaigning in 2016]]\nTrone has been active in Democratic politics and hosted fundraisers for the party.<ref name=\"Turque\">{{cite news|last1=Turque|first1=Bill|title=David Trone, owner of Total Wine & More, mulling run for Congress|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/md-politics/david-trone-owner-of-total-wine-and-more-mulling-run-for-congress/2016/01/25/ca8aa980-c3d5-11e5-8965-0607e0e265ce_story.html|accessdate=November 29, 2016|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=January 25, 2016|publisher=Nash Holdings LLC|location=Washington, D.C.|issn=0190-8286|oclc=2269358}}</ref><ref name=Marcos/> In 2014, he hosted a fundraiser for gubernatorial candidate [[Anthony G. Brown]], which was attended by former President [[Bill Clinton]], and in November 2015, he held a fundraiser at his home for the [[Democratic National Committee]], which was attended by [[Barack Obama|President Obama]].<ref name=Turque/><ref name=Stolberg/><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Kraut|first1=Aaron|title=Total Wine & More Co-Owner Hosting Wednesday Fundraiser in Potomac With President Obama|journal=Bethesda Magazine|date=November 4, 2015|url=http://www.bethesdamagazine.com/Bethesda-Beat/2015/Total-Wine-More-Co-Owner-Hosting-Wednesday-Fundraiser-in-Potomac-With-President-Obama/|accessdate=December 21, 2016}}</ref> Trone had also contributed to [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] politicians; according to a database operated by the [[National Institute on Money in State Politics]], he donated more than $150,000 to Republicans in multiple U.S. states between 2000 and 2015.<ref name=\"Republicans\">{{cite news|last1=Turque|first1=Bill|title=David Trone has donated more than $150,000 to Republicans, database shows|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/md-politics/david-trone-has-donated-more-than-150000-to-republicans-database-shows/2016/01/28/962a7048-c5e3-11e5-a4aa-f25866ba0dc6_story.html|accessdate=November 29, 2016|work=The Washington Post}}</ref> ''[[The Washington Post]]'' reported that Trone contributed more than $90,000 to Democratic state officials during the same period, and said the donations made to Republicans were to support \"legislation or regulatory changes favorable to his company\".<ref name=Republicans/> Trone said the donations \"represented the cost of doing business, especially in states with Republican-controlled state houses and governor's mansions\".<ref name=Stolberg/><ref name=Republicans/>\n\nIn January 2016, Trone entered the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] primary campaign to succeed [[Chris Van Hollen]] in [[Maryland's 8th congressional district]]. He ran on reducing unemployment and gun violence, criminal justice reform, environmental protection, and education and foreign policy. Trone pledged to support early education, work with the [[National Institutes of Health]] to reduce health care costs, improve infrastructure, and forgive more [[student loan]]s for government employees.<ref name=Gaines2016/>\n\nTrone spent more than $13 million on his unsuccessful campaign,<ref name=\"Kensington\">{{cite journal|last1=Peck|first1=Louis|title=Ex-Kensington Mayor Becomes First Candidate to Jump Into District 1 Council Race|journal=Bethesda Magazine|date=February 17, 2017|url=http://www.bethesdamagazine.com/Bethesda-Beat/2017/Ex-Kensington-Mayor-Becomes-First-Candidate-To-Jump-Into-District-1-Council-Race/|accessdate=February 23, 2017}}</ref> which became the most expensive self-funded [[United States House of Representatives|House]] campaign ever.<ref name=\"Taylor\">{{cite news|last1=Taylor|first1=Jessica|title=This Candidate Is Self-Funding More Than Anyone Ever for a Seat in Congress|url=https://www.npr.org/2016/04/23/475268587/this-candidate-is-spending-more-than-anyone-ever-for-a-seat-in-congress|accessdate=November 29, 2016|work=[[NPR]]|date=April 23, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Blumenthal\">{{cite news|last1=Blumenthal|first1=Paul|title=This Guy Spent a Record $12.7 Million Running for Congress \u2013 And Lost|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/david-trone-self-funding-maryland_us_571f92d6e4b0f309baeea63c|accessdate=November 29, 2016|work=[[The Huffington Post]]|date=April 26, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Schouten\">{{cite news|last1=Schouten|first1=Fredreka|title=Meet the man who spent $12 million on a congressional race \u2013 and lost|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/onpolitics/2016/04/27/david-trone-12-million-biggest-self-funding-house-candidate-maryland/83589854/|accessdate=November 29, 2016|work=[[USA Today]]|date=April 27, 2016|publisher=[[Gannett Company]]|location=McLean, Virginia|issn=0734-7456}}</ref><ref name=\"Peterson\">{{cite news|last1=Peterson|first1=Kristina|title=House Candidate David Trone Spent $12 Million to Finish Second in Maryland Primary|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/washwire/2016/04/27/house-candidate-david-trone-spent-12-million-to-finish-second-in-maryland-primary/|accessdate=November 29, 2016|work=The Wall Street Journal|date=April 27, 2016}}</ref> The first-time candidate said a large personal investment was necessary in order to stand out in a crowded race which included recognizable competitors, including news anchor and [[Marriott International]] executive [[Kathleen Matthews]] and election winner State Senator [[Jamie Raskin]].<ref name=Marcos/><ref name=Taylor/><ref name=\"Phillips\">{{cite news|last1=Phillips|first1=Amber|title=This man just spent a record $12 million of his own money on a House seat \u2013 and lost|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2016/04/26/this-man-just-spent-a-record-12-million-of-his-own-money-trying-to-win-a-house-set/|accessdate=November 29, 2016|work=The Washington Post|date=April 27, 2016}}</ref> Following the election, Trone told [[NPR]], \"We knew it would be very expensive. We're not surprised by what it cost at all. We anticipated that, and it was a thoughtful choice my wife and I made... It was the right decision to take no money from anybody.\"<ref name=Taylor/>\n\n==== 2018 general election====\n{{See also|2018 United States House of Representatives elections in Maryland#District 6}}\nOn August 2, 2017, Trone announced his candidacy for the Democratic nomination for [[Maryland's 6th congressional district|Maryland's 6th district]], an open seat being vacated by [[John Delaney (Maryland politician)|John Delaney]], who chose not to seek reelection and retire from Congress to focus on his [[John Delaney presidential campaign, 2020|2020 presidential campaign]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/md-politics/david-trone-jumps-into-race-to-succeed-john-delaney-in-the-us-house/2017/08/01/7d56a18e-76fb-11e7-9eac-d56bd5568db8_story.html|title=David Trone jumps into race to succeed John Delaney in the U.S. House|work=[[The Washington Post]]|last=Portnoy|first=Jenna|date=August 2, 2017|accessdate=August 2, 2017}}</ref> Trone had endorsed Delaney for President several days prior.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/davidjtrone/status/890985957981401088|title=.@JohnKDelaney has done a great job bringing people together to solve problems. He would be a fantastic President, and I'm behind him 100%!|first=David|last=Trone|date=July 28, 2017|publisher=|accessdate=July 29, 2017}}</ref> Trone told ''[[Washington Jewish Week]]'' in early 2018 that lessons learned from his prior run include not entering the race early enough and not raising money, issues that don't apply to his 2018 campaign.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://washingtonjewishweek.com/44208/in-race-for-marylands-6th-businessman-trone-highlights-opioid-crisis/featured-slider-post/ |newspaper=[[Washington Jewish Week]] |date=February 21, 2018 |first=Dan |last=Schere |title=In race for Maryland's 6th, businessman Trone highlights opioid crisis |access-date=April 9, 2018 }}</ref>\n\nTrone toured throughout Maryland in late 2017,<ref name=\"Small\">{{cite journal|last1=Metcalf|first1=Andrew|title=Trone Plans Fundraising Effort Focused on Small-Dollar Contributions|journal=[[Bethesda Magazine]]|date=August 7, 2017|url=http://www.bethesdamagazine.com/Bethesda-Beat/2017/Trone-Plans-Fundraising-Effort-Focused-on-Small-Dollar-Contributions/|accessdate=March 19, 2018}}</ref> and filed his candidacy in January 2018. His filing was accompanied by a press release expressing his support for education, [[environmental protection]]s, health care, [[Social Security (United States)|Social Security]], and [[women's rights]].<ref name=\"Larry\">{{cite news|last1=Larry|first1=Greg|title=Trone makes 6th District congressional bid|url=http://www.times-news.com/news/local_news/trone-makes-th-district-congressional-bid-official/article_5260b2c5-4f62-5d4b-9d80-40b306adb9c6.html|accessdate=March 19, 2018|date=January 10, 2018|work=[[Cumberland Times-News]]}}</ref><ref name=\"Run\">{{cite news|last1=Baker|first1=Tamela|title=Trone to run for Delaney's House seat|url=https://www.heraldmailmedia.com/news/local/trone-to-run-for-delaney-s-house-seat/article_09eed974-772c-11e7-83aa-470b77fc05f0.html|accessdate=March 19, 2018|work=[[The Herald-Mail]]|publisher=[[Schurz Communications]]|date=August 2, 2017}}</ref> Trone has also made combating the [[opioid epidemic]] a central focus of his platform,<ref name=\"Confront\">{{cite news|last1=Fritze|first1=John|title=Maryland candidate Trone calls for $100 billion to confront opioid addiction|url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/news/maryland/politics/bs-md-trone-opioid-20180108-story.html|accessdate=March 19, 2018|work=The Baltimore Sun|date=January 8, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title=Politics Roundup: Dumais' Bill to Protect Rape Victims Seen as Top Priority; Cummings Suspends Gubernatorial Campaign|journal=[[Bethesda Magazine]]|date=January 7, 2018|url=http://www.bethesdamagazine.com/Bethesda-Beat/2018/Politics-Roundup-Dumais-Bill-to-Protect-Rape-Victims-Seen-as-Top-Priority-Cummings-Suspends-Gubernatorial-Campaign/|accessdate=March 19, 2018|first1=Louis|last1=Peck|first2=Andrew|last2=Metcalf}}</ref> releasing an action plan and hosting a series of town hall meetings to address the crisis.<ref name=\"Schere2\">{{cite news|last1=Schere|first1=Dan|title=In race for Maryland's 6th, businessman Trone highlights opioid crisis|url=http://washingtonjewishweek.com/44208/in-race-for-marylands-6th-businessman-trone-highlights-opioid-crisis/featured-slider-post/|accessdate=March 19, 2018|work=[[Washington Jewish Week]]|date=February 21, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Portnoy\">{{cite news|last1=Portnoy|first1=Jenna|title=Experiences with opioid addiction and loss fuel Md. congressional hopefuls|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/md-politics/experiences-with-opioid-addiction-and-loss-fuel-md-congress-hopefuls/2018/01/20/8dad62f8-f0b2-11e7-97bf-bba379b809ab_story.html|accessdate=March 19, 2018|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=January 20, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Wolford\">{{cite news|last1=Wolford|first1=Heather B.|title=Congressional candidate hosts forum on addressing opioid crisis|url=http://www.times-news.com/news/local_news/congressional-candidate-hosts-forum-on-addressing-opioid-crisis/article_e35a3231-d93f-53f5-95a9-5cb9978e8721.html|accessdate=March 19, 2018|work=Cumberland Times-News|date=February 11, 2018}}</ref> In March 2018, Trone, gubernatorial candidate [[Rushern Baker]], and [[John Delaney (Maryland politician)|John Delaney]] organized free bus trips from Maryland to Washington, D.C., in support of the [[March for Our Lives]] demonstration.<ref name=\"Kurtz\">{{cite web|last1=Kurtz|first1=Josh|title=Political Notes: Vignarajah's Ad, Pols Paying for Buses to Anti-Gun March|url=https://www.marylandmatters.org/single-post/2018/03/22/Political-Notes-Vignarajahs-Ad-Pols-Paying-for-Buses-to-Anti-Gun-March|website=Maryland Matters|accessdate=April 18, 2016|date=March 22, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180525063257/https://www.marylandmatters.org/single-post/2018/03/22/Political-Notes-Vignarajahs-Ad-Pols-Paying-for-Buses-to-Anti-Gun-March|archive-date=May 25, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nTrone was endorsed by Baker,<ref name=\"Fritze\">{{cite news|last1=Fritze|first1=John|title=Gubernatorial candidate Rushern Baker backs David Trone in Maryland's competitive House race|url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/news/maryland/politics/bs-md-trone-baker-20180212-story.html|accessdate=March 19, 2018|work=[[The Baltimore Sun]]|date=February 12, 2018}}</ref> [[Joanne Benson]],<ref name=\"Baker\">{{cite news|last1=Baker|first1=Tamela|title=Political briefs|url=https://www.heraldmailmedia.com/news/annapolis/political_notebook/political-briefs/article_d90953bf-2b9b-5e77-b841-534733833392.html|accessdate=March 19, 2018|work=[[The Herald-Mail]]|date=February 25, 2018}}</ref> [[Anthony G. Brown]],<ref name=\"Backs\">{{cite news|last1=Fritze|first1=John|title=Anthony Brown backs David Trone in competitive House election|url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/news/maryland/politics/bs-md-brown-trone-20180306-story.html|accessdate=March 19, 2018|work=The Baltimore Sun|date=March 6, 2018}}</ref> and [[Doug Duncan]].<ref name=\"Notes\">{{cite news|last1=Baker|first1=Tamela|title=Political notes|url=https://www.heraldmailmedia.com/news/annapolis/political_notebook/political-notes/article_e07e4c5c-402b-5f97-a0f9-db9a0de29021.html|accessdate=March 19, 2018|work=The Herald-Mail|date=March 4, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn June 26, 2018, Trone won the Democratic primary election for Maryland's 6th district against seven challengers, with 40 percent of the vote.<ref name=pri18>{{cite web |url=http://elections.state.md.us/elections/2016/results/primary/gen_results_2016_3_00808.html |title=Official 2018 Gubernatorial Primary Election results for Representative in Congress: Congressional District 6 |date=July 31, 2018 |access-date=August 29, 2018 |publisher=Maryland State Board of Elections }}</ref><ref name=\"Schwartzman\">{{cite news |author1=Paul Schwartzman |author2=Jenna Portnoy |title=Trone wins Democratic primary for Delaney's House seat in Maryland |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/md-politics/trone-holds-early-lead-in-democratic-primary-for-delaneys-house-seat-in-maryland/2018/06/26/9c6354f2-77ac-11e8-80be-6d32e182a3bc_story.html |work=The Washington Post |date=June 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn the general election, Trone faced Republican Amie Hoeber and candidates from other parties.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gaines |first1=Danielle |title=Trone, Hoeber will meet at the general election in 6th District |url=https://www.fredericknewspost.com/news/continuing_coverage/election_2018/trone-hoeber-will-meet-at-the-general-election-in-th/article_70cae37e-4d0c-587e-af59-261b3a23ff12.html |work=The Frederick News-Post |date=June 26, 2018}}</ref> He received an endorsement from the ''Washington Post''.<ref>{{cite news |title=David Trone for Congress in Maryland |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/david-trone-for-congress-in-maryland/2018/10/22/6888a35c-d23e-11e8-8c22-fa2ef74bd6d6_story.html |work=The Washington Post |date=October 22, 2018}}</ref> On election day on November 6, 2018, Trone won the Congressional seat with 57.5 percent of the vote.<ref name=gen18>{{cite web |url=https://elections.maryland.gov/elections/2018/results/general/gen_results_2018_2_00806.html |title=Unofficial 2018 Gubernatorial General Election results for Representative in Congress: Congressional District 6 |date=November 8, 2018 |access-date=November 8, 2018 |publisher=Maryland State Board of Elections }}</ref><ref name=\"WTOP\">{{cite news |last1=Moore |first1=Jack |title=Maryland's 6th District: Democrat David Trone defeats GOP contender Amie Hoeber |url=https://wtop.com/maryland/2018/11/2018-election-results-maryland-congress-6th-district-david-trone-amie-hoeber/slide/1/ |work=WTOP |date=November 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.govtrack.us/congress/members/david_trone/412783|title=David Trone, Representative for Maryland's 6th Congressional District|website=GovTrack.us|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>===\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Education and Labor|Committee on Education and Labor]]'''\n**[[United States House Education Subcommittee on Higher Education and Workforce Investment|Subcommittee on Higher Education and Workforce Investment]]\n**[[United States House Education Subcommittee on Civil Rights and Human Services|Subcommittee on Civil Rights and Human Services]]\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Foreign Affairs|Committee on Foreign Affairs]]'''\n**[[United States House Subcommittee on Europe, Eurasia, Energy, and the Environment|Subcommittee on Europe, Eurasia, Energy, and the Environment]]\n**[[United States House Foreign Affairs Subcommittee on the Middle East, North Africa and International Terrorism|Subcommittee on the Middle East, North Africa and International Terrorism]]\n*'''[[United States Congress Joint Economic Committee]]'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jec.senate.gov/public/index.cfm/democrats/democratic-members|title=Democratic Members - United States Joint Economic Committee|website=www.jec.senate.gov|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\n==Electoral history==\n{{Election box begin no change\n| title = Democratic primary, Congress, Maryland 8th district, 2016 <ref name=primaryresults16>{{cite web |url=https://elections.maryland.gov/elections/2016/results/primary/gen_results_2016_3_00808.html |title=Official 2016 Presidential Primary Election results for Representative in Congress |date=May 31, 2016 |website=Maryland State Board of Elections |access-date=September 6, 2019 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = [[Jamie Raskin]]\n| party = Democratic Party (United States)\n| votes = 43,776\n| percentage = 33.6\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = '''David Trone'''\n| party = Democratic Party (United States)\n| votes = 35,400\n| percentage = 27.2\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = [[Kathleen Matthews]]\n| party = Democratic Party (United States)\n| votes = 31,186\n| percentage = 23.9\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = [[Ana Sol Gutierrez]]\n| party = Democratic Party (United States)\n| votes = 7,185\n| percentage = 5.5\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = William Jawando\n| party = Democratic Party (United States)\n| votes = 6,058\n| percentage = 4.6\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = [[Kumar Barve]]\n| party = Democratic Party (United States)\n| votes = 3,149\n| percentage = 2.4\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = David M. Anderson\n| party = Democratic Party (United States)\n| votes = 1,511\n| percentage = 1.2\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = Joel Rubin\n| party = Democratic Party (United States)\n| votes = 1,426\n| percentage = 1.1\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = Dan Bolling\n| party = Democratic Party (United States)\n| votes = 712\n| percentage = 0.5\n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n| votes = 130,403\n| percentage = 100.0\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n{{Election box begin no change\n| title = Democratic primary, Congress, Maryland 6th district, 2018\n}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = David Trone\n| party = Democratic Party (United States)\n| votes = 22855\n| percentage = 40.4\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = [[Aruna Miller]]\n| party = Democratic Party (United States)\n| votes = 17311\n| percentage = 30.6\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = [[Nadia Hashimi]]\n| party = Democratic Party (United States)\n| votes = 5871\n| percentage = 10.4\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = [[Roger Manno]]\n| party = Democratic Party (United States)\n| votes = 5788\n| percentage = 10.2\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = [[Andrew J. Duck]]\n| party = Democratic Party (United States)\n| votes = 2758\n| percentage = 4.9\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = Chris Graves\n| party = Democratic Party (United States)\n| votes = 900\n| percentage = 1.6\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = George English\n| party = Democratic Party (United States)\n| votes = 577\n| percentage = 1.0\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = Christopher Hearsey\n| party = Democratic Party (United States)\n| votes = 479\n| percentage = 0.8\n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n| votes = 56539\n| percentage = 100\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n{{Election box begin no change\n| title = Maryland's 6th congressional district, 2018\n}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = David Trone\n| party = Democratic Party (United States)\n| votes = 163,346\n| percentage = 59.0\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = Amie Hoeber\n| party = Republican Party (United States)\n| votes = 105,209\n| percentage = 38.0\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = Kevin Caldwell\n| party = Libertarian Party (United States)\n| votes = 4,972\n| percentage = 1.8\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = George Gluck\n| party = Green Party (United States)\n| votes = 3,275\n| percentage = 1.2\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = Write-ins\n| party = n/a\n| votes = 282\n| percentage = 0.1\n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n| votes = 277,084\n| percentage = 100.0\n}}\n{{Election box hold with party link without swing\n |winner    = Democratic Party (United States)\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n== Philanthropy ==\nIn addition to political contributions, Trone and his wife have supported a number of philanthropic efforts. They have been major contributors to the ACLU since 1994.<ref name=Peck/><ref name=\"Hsu\">{{cite news|last1=Hsu|first1=Spencer S.|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/public-safety/total-wine-co-founder-funds-15-million-aclu-push-to-aid-ex-convicts/2015/12/18/f046d036-a4f4-11e5-ad3f-991ce3374e23_story.html|title=Total Wine co-founder funding $15 million push to aid ex-convicts|accessdate=December 1, 2016|work=The Washington Post|date=December 21, 2015}}</ref> Their $15 million donation in 2015 supported the organization's efforts to promote criminal justice reform and improve employment opportunities for former [[prisoners]],<ref name=Turque/><ref name=Stolberg/><ref name=Hsu/> and established the Trone Center for Justice and Equality at the organization's national headquarters.<ref name=\"Root\">{{cite news|last1=Judge|first1=Monique|title=ACLU Makes the Case for Giving Formerly Incarcerated a Fair Chance at Employment|url=http://www.theroot.com/aclu-makes-the-case-for-giving-formerly-incarcerated-a-1795948983|accessdate=August 1, 2017|work=[[The Root (magazine)|The Root]]|publisher=[[Gizmodo Media Group]]|date=June 9, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=ACLU Announces New Trone Center for Criminal Justice Reform and Advisory Board of Private Sector and Education Leaders to Promote Reintegration|url=https://www.aclu.org/news/aclu-announces-new-trone-center-criminal-justice-reform-and-advisory-board-private-sector-and|publisher=[[American Civil Liberties Union]]|accessdate=August 1, 2017|date=December 21, 2016}}</ref> In 2016, the couple pledged $5 million to establish the Trone Family Public Policy Initiative Fund at their alma mater, the Wharton School of the University of Pennsylvania.<ref name=Wharton/><ref name=DiStefano/> \n\nIn mid 2017, the Trones donated $2.5 million to [[Bethesda, Maryland]]'s [[Suburban Hospital]] to support mental and behavioral health services and make improvements to the Old Georgetown Road campus. The couple's donation was inspired by their nephew's death from an opioid overdose in late 2016.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Zimmermann|first1=Joe|title=David Trone's Foundation Donates $2.5 Million to Suburban Hospital|journal=Bethesda|date=May 1, 2017|url=http://www.bethesdamagazine.com/Bethesda-Beat/2017/David-Trones-Foundation-Donates-25-Million-to-Suburban-Hospital/|accessdate=August 1, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"HighProfile\">{{cite news|last1=Turque|first1=Bill|title=David Trone stays high profile as he considers political future|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/md-politics/david-trone-stays-high-profile-as-he-considers-political-future/2017/06/15/a3344cca-5163-11e7-be25-3a519335381c_story.html|accessdate=August 1, 2017|work=The Washington Post|date=June 15, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Metcalf\">{{cite journal|last1=Metcalf|first1=Andrew|title=Trone Donates to Legal Fund to Assist Local Families Potentially Impacted by Trump's Proposed Travel Ban|journal=Bethesda|date=June 1, 2017|url=http://www.bethesdamagazine.com/Bethesda-Beat/2017/Trone-Donates-to-Legal-Fund-To-Assist-Local-Families-Potentially-Impacted-by-Trumps-Proposed-Travel-Ban/|accessdate=July 6, 2017}}</ref> The David and June Trone Family Foundation contributed $100,000 to the [[Catholic Legal Immigration Network]] in mid 2017 to support locals affected by Trump's travel ban, which the couple called \"outrageously egregious\". The Trones also donated to the ACLU's Montgomery County affiliate, the Latino immigrant organization CASA, and Interfaith Works.<ref name=Metcalf/><ref name=\"LegalAid\">{{cite news|last1=Turque|first1=Bill|title=Trone to fund legal aid for families who could be impacted by travel ban|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/md-politics/trone-to-fund-legal-aid-for-families-who-could-be-impacted-by-travel-ban/2017/06/01/9745caee-46ee-11e7-bcde-624ad94170ab_story.html|accessdate=August 1, 2017|work=The Washington Post|date=June 1, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Kazour\">{{cite news|last1=Kazour|first1=Mona|title=Legal Assistance for Montgomery County Families Affected by Trump Travel Ban|url=https://patch.com/maryland/bethesda-chevychase/legal-assistance-montgomery-county-families-affected-trump-travel-ban|accessdate=August 1, 2017|work=Bethesda Patch|date=June 2, 2017}}</ref>\n\nTrone's contributions to Furman University include a $5 million grant for a student center and to create men's and women's lacrosse teams, and the lead $500,000 gift for the Riley Foundation's endowment to support disadvantaged South Carolina students.<ref name=Felicien/><ref name=\"Dabbs\">{{cite web|last1=Dabbs|first1=Kate Hofler|first2=Evan|last2=Hildreth|title=Raising Up Riley: An Endowment for the Riley Institute|url=https://news.furman.edu/2012/12/01/raising-up-riley-an-endowment-for-the-riley-institute/|publisher=Furman University|accessdate=February 23, 2017|date=December 1, 2012}}</ref> The Trone Student Center was dedicated in 2013 and named for Trone and his wife, in honor of their $3.5 million contribution.<ref name=Furman/>\n\n== Personal life ==\nTrone serves as chair of the Trone Private Sector and Education Advisory Council at the ACLU Trone Center.<ref name=Hsu/><ref name=\"Leadership\">{{cite journal|title=Business Notes: Leadership Montgomery Announces 2018 Participants|journal=Bethesda|date=August 1, 2017|url=http://www.bethesdamagazine.com/Bethesda-Beat/2017/Business-Notes-Leadership-Montgomery-Announces-2018-Participants/|accessdate=July 6, 2017}}</ref> He has served on the [[Bullis School]]'s board of trustees since 2006.<ref>{{cite web|title=Trustees|url=http://www.bullis.org/page.cfm?p=963|publisher=[[Bullis School]]|accessdate=August 1, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170801200150/http://www.bullis.org/page.cfm?p=963|archive-date=August 1, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Kids Enjoy Exercise Now (KEEN) Greater DC gave Trone the \"Distinguished Service Award\" for his many contributions to the organization, which provides recreational programs for children with developmental and physical disabilities.<ref name=\"KEEN\">{{cite web|title=Annual Report 2012|url=http://www.keengreaterdc.org/sites/default/files/KEENGDC_Annual_Report_2012_Final.pdf|publisher=KEEN Greater DC|accessdate=December 21, 2016|format=PDF|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160127194447/http://www.keengreaterdc.org/sites/default/files/KEENGDC_Annual_Report_2012_Final.pdf|archive-date=January 27, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> He was honored at the 2014 [[Ernst & Young]] Entrepreneur of the Year Awards Greater Washington, in the \"large company\" category.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Koeppen|first1=Brynn|title=Ernst and Young Entrepreneur of the Year Awards Greater Washington Revealed: ECS Federal, Matchbox Among Winners|url=http://www.washingtonexec.com/2014/06/ernst-young-entrepreneur-year-awards-greater-washington-revealed-ecs-federal-matchbox-among-winners/|accessdate=December 21, 2016|work=WashingtonExec|date=June 20, 2014}}</ref> In 2015, Trone was invited by the [[American University]]'s Kennedy Political Union and the [[Kogod School of Business]] to speak to students and faculty about entrepreneurship and business leadership.<ref name=Rozen/> He was awarded the [[Anti-Defamation League]]'s annual achievement award in 2016.<ref name=\"Schere\">{{cite journal|last1=Schere|first1=Daniel|title=Did ADL endorse David Trone?|url=http://washingtonjewishweek.com/30718/did-adl-endorse-david-trone/featured-slider-post/|accessdate=December 21, 2016|work=[[Washington Jewish Week]]|date=April 20, 2016|issn=0746-9373}}</ref> In 2016, Trone joined the boards of [[American University]] and the Montgomery County Chamber of Commerce.<ref>American University: * {{cite web|title=Current Trustees|url=http://www.american.edu/trustees/Current-Trustees.cfm|publisher=[[American University]]|accessdate=February 23, 2017}} * {{cite web|title=Board of Trustees Late Fall 2016 Meeting Summary|url=http://www.american.edu/trustees/Announcement-November-30-2016.cfm|publisher=American University|accessdate=February 23, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Board of Directors|url=http://www.mcccmd.com/about-mccc/board-directory/board-directors|publisher=Montgomery County Chamber of Commerce|accessdate=February 23, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170801200139/http://www.mcccmd.com/about-mccc/board-directory/board-directors|archive-date=August 1, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Trone received Furman University's Carl F. Kohrt Distinguished Alumni Award, which is presented \"to an alumnus in recognition of significant professional or personal accomplishments and in gratitude for continued loyalty\".<ref name=\"Felicien\">{{cite news|last1=Felicien|first1=Tesalon|title=Total Wine and More's David Trone to receive distinguished Furman award|url=http://www.greenvilleonline.com/story/money/business/2017/02/21/total-wine-and-mores-david-trone-receive-distinguished-furman-award/98190412/|accessdate=February 23, 2017|work=[[The Greenville News]]|publisher=Gannett Company|location=Greenville, South Carolina}}</ref> He served on Furman University's board of trustees from 2010 to 2016.<ref name=Felicien/>\n\nDuring his 2018 campaign, Trone was diagnosed with cancer and underwent chemotherapy and surgery to remove a kidney; he was declared cancer-free by October.<ref name=\"cancer\">{{cite news |last1=Schwartzman |first1=Paul |title=David Trone says he is 'cancer free' three weeks after surgery |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/md-politics/trone-declares-himself-cancer-free-three-weeks-after-surgery/2018/10/02/3d694146-c680-11e8-b1ed-1d2d65b86d0c_story.html |work=The Washington Post |date=October 2, 2018}}</ref>\n\n{{as of|2016}}, the Trones live in [[Potomac, Maryland]].<ref name=Turque/><ref name=\"Spends\">{{cite news|last1=Turque|first1=Bill|title=David Trone spends $9.1 million of his own money on Md. congressional race|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/md-politics/david-trone-spends-91-million-of-his-own-money-on-md-congressional-race/2016/04/12/29f5827c-00c2-11e6-b823-707c79ce3504_story.html|accessdate=December 1, 2016|work=The Washington Post|date=April 12, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title=Total Wine co-owner will fund his run for Congress|journal=Washington Business Journal|date=January 28, 2016|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/washington/morning_call/2016/01/total-wine-coowner-will-fund-his-run-for-congress.html|accessdate=December 1, 2016|publisher=[[American City Business Journals]]}}</ref>\nTrone was raised Lutheran. His wife and all four children are Jewish and attend Temple Beth Ami in Rockville.<ref name=\"WJW\">{{cite journal|last1=Schere|first1=Dan|title=In race for Maryland's 6th, businessman Trone highlights opioid crisis|journal=Washington Jewish Week|date=February 21, 2018|url=http://washingtonjewishweek.com/44208/in-race-for-marylands-6th-businessman-trone-highlights-opioid-crisis/featured-slider-post/|accessdate=April 18, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Cortellessa\">{{cite news|last1=Cortellessa|first1=Eric|title=The Maryland wine mogul who is staking his fortune on reaching Capitol Hill|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/the-maryland-wine-mogul-who-is-staking-his-fortune-on-reaching-capitol-hill/|accessdate=May 25, 2018|work=[[The Times of Israel]]|date=March 24, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of people from Potomac, Maryland]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{Cite news|url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/news/opinion/oped/bs-ed-op-0615-opioid-home-20170612-story.html|first=David|last=Trone|title=The opioid crisis hits home for Maryland man|date=June 14, 2017|work=[[The Baltimore Sun]]}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://trone.house.gov/ Congressman David Trone] official U.S. House website\n*[https://www.davidtrone.com/ David Trone for Congress]\n{{CongLinks|votesmart=167336|congbio=T000483|fec=H6MD08549|congress=david-trone/T000483}}\n* {{Commons category-inline|David Trone}}\n* {{Cite journal|url=http://mydigitalpublication.com/publication/?i=394294#%7Bissue_id:394294,page:0%7D|title=The Art of Leadership|work=Montgomery Magazine|date=April\u2013May 2017}}\n* {{C-SPAN|David Trone}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[John Delaney (Maryland politician)|John Delaney]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[List of United States Representatives from Maryland|U.S. House of Representatives]]<br>from [[Maryland's 6th congressional district]]|years=2019\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-prec|usa}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Lori Trahan]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Seniority in the United States House of Representatives|United States Representatives by seniority]]|years=420th}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Lauren Underwood]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{MD-FedRep}}\n{{USHouseCurrent}}\n{{USCongRep-start|congresses= 116th [[United States Congress]] |state=[[Maryland]]}}\n{{USCongRep/MD/116}}\n{{USCongRep-end}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Trone, David}}\n[[Category:1950s births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:21st-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:American company founders]]\n[[Category:American philanthropists]]\n[[Category:American retail chief executives]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Maryland]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Furman University alumni]]\n[[Category:Kidney cancer survivors]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Maryland Democrats]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from Maryland]]\n[[Category:People from Adams County, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:People from Potomac, Maryland]]\n[[Category:Retail company founders]]\n[[Category:Wharton School of the University of Pennsylvania alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American businessman and politician}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name        = David Trone\n|image       = David Trone official photo.jpg\n|state       = [[Maryland]]\n|district    = {{ushr|MD|6|6th}}\n|term_start  = January 3, 2019\n|term_end    = \n|predecessor = [[John Delaney (Maryland politician)|John Delaney]]\n|successor   = \n|birth_name  = David John Trone\n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1955|9|21}}\n|birth_place = [[Cheverly, Maryland]], U.S.\n|death_date  = \n|death_place = \n|party       = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|spouse      = June Trone\n|children    = 4\n|education   = [[Furman University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br>[[University of Pennsylvania]] ([[Master of Business Administration|MBA]])\n|website     = {{url|trone.house.gov|House website}}\n}}\n'''David John Trone''' (born September 21, 1955)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.archives.upenn.edu/primdocs/upg/upg7/upg7_1985.pdf#page=34 |publisher=University of Pennsylvania |page=34 |title=Two Hundred Twenty-Ninth Commencement for the Conferring of Degrees |date=May 20, 1985 |access-date=June 30, 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://votesmart.org/candidate/biography/167336/david-trone |title=David Trone's Biography |access-date=June 30, 2018 |website=Vote Smart }}</ref> is an American businessman and politician, serving as the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for [[Maryland's 6th congressional district]]. The district includes most of the western third of the state, but the bulk of its population is located in the outer northern suburbs of [[Washington, D. C.]]. He co-founded and co-owns [[Total Wine & More]], along with his brother, and served as the company's president until December 2016.\n\nIn 2016, Trone spent more than $13 million on his unsuccessful [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] primary campaign to succeed [[Chris Van Hollen]] in [[Maryland's 8th congressional district]], setting a record for the most expensive self-funded [[United States House of Representatives|House]] campaign. In 2018, Trone was the Democratic nominee for 6th district, and won the general election to succeed [[John Delaney (Maryland politician)|John Delaney]] beginning in 2019.\n\n== Early life and education ==\nTrone was born in Maryland and raised on a {{Convert|200|acre|ha|adj=on}} farm in [[East Berlin, Pennsylvania]],<ref name=Teague>{{Cite news|publisher=[[Dow Jones & Company]]|issn=0099-9660|oclc=781541372|location=New York City|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-man-behind-americas-wine-superstore-1481754128|title=The Man Behind 'America's Wine Superstore'|date=December 14, 2016|first=Lettie|last=Teague|accessdate=December 20, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Heath\">{{cite news|last1=Heath|first1=Thomas|title=Value Added: Potomac's Total Wine|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/economy/value-added-potomacs-total-wine/2011/12/14/gIQARxW02O_story.html|accessdate=December 1, 2016|work=The Washington Post|date=December 18, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"Rozen\">{{cite news|last1=Rozen|first1=Courtney|title=David Trone encourages students to embrace failure and experiment with innovative business ventures at KPU event|url=http://www.theeagleonline.com/article/2015/11/david-trone-kpu-event|accessdate=December 1, 2016|work=The Eagle|publisher=[[American University]]|date=November 24, 2015}}</ref> where his father, Thomas, ran a chicken and hog operation.<ref name=Heath/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-39482834.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181002064627/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-39482834.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=October 2, 2018|title=For Wine Mogul David Trone, Congressional Race Is Unfinished Business (Posted 2016-04-03 23:45:35); First in a Series of Profiles of Democratic Primary Candidates in Maryland's 8th Congressional District|work=The Washington Post|url-access=subscription |via=[[HighBeam Research]]|date=April 3, 2016|accessdate=January 30, 2017|last=Turque|first=Bill}}</ref> Thomas also owned a soda and beer store. When Trone's parents separated, his father kept the farm and his mother took over the store.<ref name=Heath/> Thomas and his farm went into bankruptcy,<ref name=\"Stolberg\">{{cite news|last1=Stolberg|first1=Sheryl Gay|title=Maryland House Race a 'Caldron of Power Couples and Washington, D.C., Politics'|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/03/06/us/a-clamor-for-a-safe-district-with-a-short-commute.html|accessdate=December 1, 2016|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=March 5, 2016|issn=0362-4331|oclc=1645522}}</ref><ref name=\"Gaines2016\">{{cite news|last1=Gaines|first1=Danielle E.|title=U.S. House race: First-time candidate Trone looks to bring business acumen to Congress|url=http://www.fredericknewspost.com/news/continuing_coverage/election_2016/u-s-house-race-first-time-candidate-trone-looks-to/article_e335f779-162f-5651-8fc0-81627dcc5bf0.html|accessdate=December 1, 2016|work=[[Frederick News-Post]]|publisher=Randall Family, LLC|date=March 8, 2016|oclc=31371730|location=Frederick, Maryland}}</ref> but Trone kept working at his mother's store.<ref name=Heath/>\n\nTrone graduated magna cum laude, [[Phi Beta Kappa Society|Phi Beta Kappa]], from [[Furman University]] in 1977,<ref name=\"Pulcini\">{{cite web|last1=Pulcini|first1=Max|title=Wine Retailer CEO Speaks at Kogod Leadership Speaker Series|url=http://www.metromba.com/2016/01/wine-retailer-ceo-speaks-kogod-leadership-speaker-series/|website=MetroMBA|accessdate=February 23, 2017|date=January 21, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Furman\">{{cite web|title=Furman Dedicates Trone Student Center|url=http://news.furman.edu/2013/09/20/trone-student-center-dedication/|publisher=[[Furman University]]|accessdate=December 21, 2016|date=September 20, 2013}}</ref> and earned his [[Master of Business Administration|MBA]] in 1985 from the [[Wharton School of the University of Pennsylvania]].<ref name=\"Wharton\">{{cite web|title=The Penn Wharton Public Policy Initiative Announces $5 Million Gift from David Trone and June Malament Trone|url=https://news.wharton.upenn.edu/press-releases/2016/03/the-penn-wharton-public-policy-initiative-announces-5-million-gift-from-david-trone-and-june-malament-trone/|publisher=[[Wharton School of the University of Pennsylvania]]|accessdate=December 1, 2016|date=March 8, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Marcos\">{{cite news|last1=Marcos|first1=Cristina|title=Candidate who spent $12M loses Md. House race|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/ballot-box/house-races/277728-candidate-who-spent-12m-loses-md-house-race|accessdate=November 29, 2016|work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]|publisher=News Communications, Inc.|date=April 26, 2016|location=Washington, D.C.|issn=1521-1568}}</ref><ref name=\"DiStefano\">{{cite news|last1=DiStefano|first1=Joseph N.|title=Wine stores owner gives Wharton $5M to probe laws, runs for Congress|url=http://www.philly.com/philly/blogs/inq-phillydeals/Discount-liquor-dealer-gives-Wharton-5-million.html|accessdate=December 1, 2016|work=[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]]|date=March 8, 2016|issn=0885-6613}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n=== Total Wine & More ===\n{{Main|Total Wine & More}}\n\nHaving seen the potential of the beer sales at his mother's store,<ref name=Heath/> Trone began his career by founding the beer-only retailer Beer World in Pennsylvania in 1984, during his second semester of graduate school.<ref name=\"Doss\">{{cite news|last1=Doss|first1=Laine|title=Total Wine President David Trone: \"8000 wines, 3000 spirits, and 3000 beers\"|url=http://www.miaminewtimes.com/restaurants/total-wine-president-david-trone-8000-wines-3000-spirits-and-3000-beers-7975272|accessdate=December 1, 2016|work=[[Miami New Times]]|publisher=[[Voice Media Group]]|date=October 16, 2015}}</ref> Months before graduating from Wharton, in 1985, Trone expanded into the [[Pittsburgh metropolitan area]]. Over time, he opened additional stores, called Beer and Pop Warehouse and, later, Beer World, which were owned by friends and family members because Pennsylvania state law prohibited individuals from owning more than one beer retail outlet.<ref name=\"Peck\">{{cite journal|last1=Peck|first1=Louis|title=David Trone's Path to Business Success Included Three Arrests Involving Disputes with State Authorities|journal=Bethesda Magazine|date=February 22, 2016|url=http://www.bethesdamagazine.com/Bethesda-Beat/Web-2016/David-Trones-Path-to-Business-Success-Included-Three-Arrests-Involving-Disputes-with-State-Authorities/|accessdate=December 2, 2016}}</ref>\n\nTrone, with the assistance of his brother Robert, then opened two stores in Delaware in 1991, adding wine and spirits to the company's offerings.<ref name=Rozen/><ref name=\"Tuttle\">{{cite journal|last1=Tuttle|first1=Brad|title=Your Local Dinky Mom and Pop Liquor Shop Is in Major Trouble|journal=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|date=March 27, 2014|url=http://time.com/40617/your-local-dinky-mom-and-pop-liquor-shop-is-in-major-trouble/|accessdate=December 1, 2016}}</ref> Using knowledge acquired at Wharton, the brothers chose to replicate the family store's model across Pennsylvania. The beverage company had slim margins, but was immediately profitable and allowed the brothers to focus on operations.<ref name=Heath/> The brothers familiarized themselves with regulators and industry leaders, and began changing laws that restrict wholesalers from offering retailers discounts in exchange for large volume purchases, among others in their attempt to promote beverage consumption.<ref name=Heath/>\n\nThe business has since expanded into what is known today as [[Total Wine & More]], the largest privately owned beer, wine, and spirits retailer in the United States.<ref name=\"Halkias\">{{cite news|last1=Halkias|first1=Maria|title=Big-box wine retailers enter Dallas in a huge way|url=http://www.dallasnews.com/business/retail/2012/05/26/big-box-wine-retailers-enter-dallas-in-a-huge-way|accessdate=January 30, 2017|work=[[The Dallas Morning News]]|publisher=[[A. H. Belo]]|date=May 2012|issn=1553-846X}}</ref><ref name=\"Morris\">{{cite news|last1=Morris|first1=Asia|title=Family-Owned Retail Giant Total Wine & More Opens First Long Beach Location|url=https://lbpost.com/food/2000006254-family-owned-retail-giant-total-wine-more-opens-first-store-in-long-beach|accessdate=January 30, 2017|work=Long Beach Post|date=June 4, 2015}}</ref>  In December 2016, Trone gave up his title of president to chief executive Kevin Peters.<ref name=Teague/>\n\n====Arrests and indictments====\nBeginning in 1989 and for the following three years, Pennsylvania authorities arrested Trone three times following complaints from an association of smaller, individually owned stores.<ref name=Peck/><ref name=\"globe\">{{cite web|author1=Dan Adams, Globe staff|title=For Total Wine, it's total war against alcohol regulations|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/business/2017/05/20/for-total-wine-total-war-against-alcohol-regulations/lj09FZ4pg1oDEWJFqKuyZM/story.html|publisher=[[Boston Globe]]|accessdate=August 10, 2017|date=May 20, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"NABCA\">{{cite web|title=Daily News Update: From Boston Globe|url=http://www.nabca.org/assets/docs/DNU_MAY_23.pdf|website=NABCA|publisher=National Alcohol Beverage Control Association|accessdate=August 10, 2017|date=May 23, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170810205854/http://www.nabca.org/assets/docs/DNU_MAY_23.pdf|archive-date=August 10, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>  One arrest was for negotiating volume discounts on behalf of multiple stores and illegally advertising beer prices,<ref name=Peck/> and another was for circumventing state transportation regulations. These charges were later dismissed.<ref name=Peck/>\n\nIn 1992, Trone, his wife, June, and brother were indicted by a grand jury in [[Dauphin County, Pennsylvania]], for owning multiple stores through Trone's consulting company, among other charges, all of which were later dropped and expunged.<ref name=\"Gazette\">{{cite news|last1=Gazette|title=Legal disputes not likely to hurt wine-beer superstore application|url=http://www.gazette.net/gazette_archive/1997/199725/montgomerycty/county/a58155-1.html|accessdate=December 1, 2016|work=[[The Gazette (Maryland)|The Gazette]]|date=June 18, 1997|location=Gaithersburg, Maryland}}{{Dead link|date=November 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> In 1994, a state judge dismissed 19 of the 23 counts based on \"prosecutorial overreaching\", and the remaining counts were withdrawn after Trone paid a $40,000 fee to cover investigation costs.<ref name=Peck/><ref name=Gazette/>\n\nDuring these legal proceedings, the [[Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco, Firearms and Explosives]] (ATF) broke the law by providing records of his consulting firm to government officials, prompting Trone to sue the agency in federal court. Trone won and was awarded $400,000. The lawyer who had represented Trone also served as a national board member of the [[American Civil Liberties Union]] (ACLU), which would begin the start of a long-term relationship between Trone and the nonpartisan, non-profit organization.<ref name=Peck/> The Trones' difficulties in Pennsylvania prompted them to leave the state; Total Wine & More grew from the remaining two stores in Delaware and an additional retail outlet in New Jersey, which had been opened by Trone during the early 1990s.<ref name=Peck/>\n\nIn 2016, Total Wine was served with a license suspension by the Massachusetts Alcoholic Beverages Control Commission for selling liquor below its costs.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.metrowestdailynews.com/news/20170201/total-wine-in-natick-everett-suing-state |title=Total Wine in Natick, Everett suing state |newspaper=MetroWest Daily News |date=February 1, 2016 |access-date=November 20, 2017 |first=Brian |last=Benson }}</ref> The company appealed the commission's decision, and in mid 2017 the Suffolk Superior Court sided with Total Wine.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Benson|first1=Brian|title=Natick: Judge sides with Total Wine & More in pricing dispute|url=http://www.metrowestdailynews.com/news/20170726/natick-judge-sides-with-total-wine-amp-more-in-pricing-dispute|accessdate=January 22, 2018|work=[[The MetroWest Daily News]]|date=July 26, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== U.S. House of Representatives ==\n=== Elections ===\n==== 2016 primary election ====\n{{See also|2016 United States House of Representatives elections in Maryland#District 8}}\n[[File:David Trone campaigning at the red line in Rockville in 2016.JPG|thumb|upright|Trone campaigning in 2016]]\nTrone has been active in Democratic politics and hosted fundraisers for the party.<ref name=\"Turque\">{{cite news|last1=Turque|first1=Bill|title=David Trone, owner of Total Wine & More, mulling run for Congress|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/md-politics/david-trone-owner-of-total-wine-and-more-mulling-run-for-congress/2016/01/25/ca8aa980-c3d5-11e5-8965-0607e0e265ce_story.html|accessdate=November 29, 2016|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=January 25, 2016|publisher=Nash Holdings LLC|location=Washington, D.C.|issn=0190-8286|oclc=2269358}}</ref><ref name=Marcos/> In 2014, he hosted a fundraiser for gubernatorial candidate [[Anthony G. Brown]], which was attended by former President [[Bill Clinton]], and in November 2015, he held a fundraiser at his home for the [[Democratic National Committee]], which was attended by [[Barack Obama|President Obama]].<ref name=Turque/><ref name=Stolberg/><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Kraut|first1=Aaron|title=Total Wine & More Co-Owner Hosting Wednesday Fundraiser in Potomac With President Obama|journal=Bethesda Magazine|date=November 4, 2015|url=http://www.bethesdamagazine.com/Bethesda-Beat/2015/Total-Wine-More-Co-Owner-Hosting-Wednesday-Fundraiser-in-Potomac-With-President-Obama/|accessdate=December 21, 2016}}</ref> Trone had also contributed to [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] politicians; according to a database operated by the [[National Institute on Money in State Politics]], he donated more than $150,000 to Republicans in multiple U.S. states between 2000 and 2015.<ref name=\"Republicans\">{{cite news|last1=Turque|first1=Bill|title=David Trone has donated more than $150,000 to Republicans, database shows|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/md-politics/david-trone-has-donated-more-than-150000-to-republicans-database-shows/2016/01/28/962a7048-c5e3-11e5-a4aa-f25866ba0dc6_story.html|accessdate=November 29, 2016|work=The Washington Post}}</ref> ''[[The Washington Post]]'' reported that Trone contributed more than $90,000 to Democratic state officials during the same period, and said the donations made to Republicans were to support \"legislation or regulatory changes favorable to his company\".<ref name=Republicans/> Trone said the donations \"represented the cost of doing business, especially in states with Republican-controlled state houses and governor's mansions\".<ref name=Stolberg/><ref name=Republicans/>\n\nIn January 2016, Trone entered the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] primary campaign to succeed [[Chris Van Hollen]] in [[Maryland's 8th congressional district]]. He ran on reducing unemployment and gun violence, criminal justice reform, environmental protection, and education and foreign policy. Trone pledged to support early education, work with the [[National Institutes of Health]] to reduce health care costs, improve infrastructure, and forgive more [[student loan]]s for government employees.<ref name=Gaines2016/>\n\nTrone spent more than $13 million on his unsuccessful campaign,<ref name=\"Kensington\">{{cite journal|last1=Peck|first1=Louis|title=Ex-Kensington Mayor Becomes First Candidate to Jump Into District 1 Council Race|journal=Bethesda Magazine|date=February 17, 2017|url=http://www.bethesdamagazine.com/Bethesda-Beat/2017/Ex-Kensington-Mayor-Becomes-First-Candidate-To-Jump-Into-District-1-Council-Race/|accessdate=February 23, 2017}}</ref> which became the most expensive self-funded [[United States House of Representatives|House]] campaign ever.<ref name=\"Taylor\">{{cite news|last1=Taylor|first1=Jessica|title=This Candidate Is Self-Funding More Than Anyone Ever for a Seat in Congress|url=https://www.npr.org/2016/04/23/475268587/this-candidate-is-spending-more-than-anyone-ever-for-a-seat-in-congress|accessdate=November 29, 2016|work=[[NPR]]|date=April 23, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Blumenthal\">{{cite news|last1=Blumenthal|first1=Paul|title=This Guy Spent a Record $12.7 Million Running for Congress \u2013 And Lost|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/david-trone-self-funding-maryland_us_571f92d6e4b0f309baeea63c|accessdate=November 29, 2016|work=[[The Huffington Post]]|date=April 26, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Schouten\">{{cite news|last1=Schouten|first1=Fredreka|title=Meet the man who spent $12 million on a congressional race \u2013 and lost|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/onpolitics/2016/04/27/david-trone-12-million-biggest-self-funding-house-candidate-maryland/83589854/|accessdate=November 29, 2016|work=[[USA Today]]|date=April 27, 2016|publisher=[[Gannett Company]]|location=McLean, Virginia|issn=0734-7456}}</ref><ref name=\"Peterson\">{{cite news|last1=Peterson|first1=Kristina|title=House Candidate David Trone Spent $12 Million to Finish Second in Maryland Primary|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/washwire/2016/04/27/house-candidate-david-trone-spent-12-million-to-finish-second-in-maryland-primary/|accessdate=November 29, 2016|work=The Wall Street Journal|date=April 27, 2016}}</ref> The first-time candidate said a large personal investment was necessary in order to stand out in a crowded race which included recognizable competitors, including news anchor and [[Marriott International]] executive [[Kathleen Matthews]] and election winner State Senator [[Jamie Raskin]].<ref name=Marcos/><ref name=Taylor/><ref name=\"Phillips\">{{cite news|last1=Phillips|first1=Amber|title=This man just spent a record $12 million of his own money on a House seat \u2013 and lost|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2016/04/26/this-man-just-spent-a-record-12-million-of-his-own-money-trying-to-win-a-house-set/|accessdate=November 29, 2016|work=The Washington Post|date=April 27, 2016}}</ref> Following the election, Trone told [[NPR]], \"We knew it would be very expensive. We're not surprised by what it cost at all. We anticipated that, and it was a thoughtful choice my wife and I made... It was the right decision to take no money from anybody.\"<ref name=Taylor/>\n\n==== 2018 general election====\n{{See also|2018 United States House of Representatives elections in Maryland#District 6}}\nOn August 2, 2017, Trone announced his candidacy for the Democratic nomination for [[Maryland's 6th congressional district|Maryland's 6th district]], an open seat being vacated by [[John Delaney (Maryland politician)|John Delaney]], who chose not to seek reelection and retire from Congress to focus on his [[John Delaney presidential campaign, 2020|2020 presidential campaign]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/md-politics/david-trone-jumps-into-race-to-succeed-john-delaney-in-the-us-house/2017/08/01/7d56a18e-76fb-11e7-9eac-d56bd5568db8_story.html|title=David Trone jumps into race to succeed John Delaney in the U.S. House|work=[[The Washington Post]]|last=Portnoy|first=Jenna|date=August 2, 2017|accessdate=August 2, 2017}}</ref> Trone had endorsed Delaney for President several days prior.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/davidjtrone/status/890985957981401088|title=.@JohnKDelaney has done a great job bringing people together to solve problems. He would be a fantastic President, and I'm behind him 100%!|first=David|last=Trone|date=July 28, 2017|publisher=|accessdate=July 29, 2017}}</ref> Trone told ''[[Washington Jewish Week]]'' in early 2018 that lessons learned from his prior run include not entering the race early enough and not raising money, issues that don't apply to his 2018 campaign.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://washingtonjewishweek.com/44208/in-race-for-marylands-6th-businessman-trone-highlights-opioid-crisis/featured-slider-post/ |newspaper=[[Washington Jewish Week]] |date=February 21, 2018 |first=Dan |last=Schere |title=In race for Maryland's 6th, businessman Trone highlights opioid crisis |access-date=April 9, 2018 }}</ref>\n\nTrone toured throughout Maryland in late 2017,<ref name=\"Small\">{{cite journal|last1=Metcalf|first1=Andrew|title=Trone Plans Fundraising Effort Focused on Small-Dollar Contributions|journal=[[Bethesda Magazine]]|date=August 7, 2017|url=http://www.bethesdamagazine.com/Bethesda-Beat/2017/Trone-Plans-Fundraising-Effort-Focused-on-Small-Dollar-Contributions/|accessdate=March 19, 2018}}</ref> and filed his candidacy in January 2018. His filing was accompanied by a press release expressing his support for education, [[environmental protection]]s, health care, [[Social Security (United States)|Social Security]], and [[women's rights]].<ref name=\"Larry\">{{cite news|last1=Larry|first1=Greg|title=Trone makes 6th District congressional bid|url=http://www.times-news.com/news/local_news/trone-makes-th-district-congressional-bid-official/article_5260b2c5-4f62-5d4b-9d80-40b306adb9c6.html|accessdate=March 19, 2018|date=January 10, 2018|work=[[Cumberland Times-News]]}}</ref><ref name=\"Run\">{{cite news|last1=Baker|first1=Tamela|title=Trone to run for Delaney's House seat|url=https://www.heraldmailmedia.com/news/local/trone-to-run-for-delaney-s-house-seat/article_09eed974-772c-11e7-83aa-470b77fc05f0.html|accessdate=March 19, 2018|work=[[The Herald-Mail]]|publisher=[[Schurz Communications]]|date=August 2, 2017}}</ref> Trone has also made combating the [[opioid epidemic]] a central focus of his platform,<ref name=\"Confront\">{{cite news|last1=Fritze|first1=John|title=Maryland candidate Trone calls for $100 billion to confront opioid addiction|url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/news/maryland/politics/bs-md-trone-opioid-20180108-story.html|accessdate=March 19, 2018|work=The Baltimore Sun|date=January 8, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title=Politics Roundup: Dumais' Bill to Protect Rape Victims Seen as Top Priority; Cummings Suspends Gubernatorial Campaign|journal=[[Bethesda Magazine]]|date=January 7, 2018|url=http://www.bethesdamagazine.com/Bethesda-Beat/2018/Politics-Roundup-Dumais-Bill-to-Protect-Rape-Victims-Seen-as-Top-Priority-Cummings-Suspends-Gubernatorial-Campaign/|accessdate=March 19, 2018|first1=Louis|last1=Peck|first2=Andrew|last2=Metcalf}}</ref> releasing an action plan and hosting a series of town hall meetings to address the crisis.<ref name=\"Schere2\">{{cite news|last1=Schere|first1=Dan|title=In race for Maryland's 6th, businessman Trone highlights opioid crisis|url=http://washingtonjewishweek.com/44208/in-race-for-marylands-6th-businessman-trone-highlights-opioid-crisis/featured-slider-post/|accessdate=March 19, 2018|work=[[Washington Jewish Week]]|date=February 21, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Portnoy\">{{cite news|last1=Portnoy|first1=Jenna|title=Experiences with opioid addiction and loss fuel Md. congressional hopefuls|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/md-politics/experiences-with-opioid-addiction-and-loss-fuel-md-congress-hopefuls/2018/01/20/8dad62f8-f0b2-11e7-97bf-bba379b809ab_story.html|accessdate=March 19, 2018|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=January 20, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Wolford\">{{cite news|last1=Wolford|first1=Heather B.|title=Congressional candidate hosts forum on addressing opioid crisis|url=http://www.times-news.com/news/local_news/congressional-candidate-hosts-forum-on-addressing-opioid-crisis/article_e35a3231-d93f-53f5-95a9-5cb9978e8721.html|accessdate=March 19, 2018|work=Cumberland Times-News|date=February 11, 2018}}</ref> In March 2018, Trone, gubernatorial candidate [[Rushern Baker]], and [[John Delaney (Maryland politician)|John Delaney]] organized free bus trips from Maryland to Washington, D.C., in support of the [[March for Our Lives]] demonstration.<ref name=\"Kurtz\">{{cite web|last1=Kurtz|first1=Josh|title=Political Notes: Vignarajah's Ad, Pols Paying for Buses to Anti-Gun March|url=https://www.marylandmatters.org/single-post/2018/03/22/Political-Notes-Vignarajahs-Ad-Pols-Paying-for-Buses-to-Anti-Gun-March|website=Maryland Matters|accessdate=April 18, 2016|date=March 22, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180525063257/https://www.marylandmatters.org/single-post/2018/03/22/Political-Notes-Vignarajahs-Ad-Pols-Paying-for-Buses-to-Anti-Gun-March|archive-date=May 25, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nTrone was endorsed by Baker,<ref name=\"Fritze\">{{cite news|last1=Fritze|first1=John|title=Gubernatorial candidate Rushern Baker backs David Trone in Maryland's competitive House race|url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/news/maryland/politics/bs-md-trone-baker-20180212-story.html|accessdate=March 19, 2018|work=[[The Baltimore Sun]]|date=February 12, 2018}}</ref> [[Joanne Benson]],<ref name=\"Baker\">{{cite news|last1=Baker|first1=Tamela|title=Political briefs|url=https://www.heraldmailmedia.com/news/annapolis/political_notebook/political-briefs/article_d90953bf-2b9b-5e77-b841-534733833392.html|accessdate=March 19, 2018|work=[[The Herald-Mail]]|date=February 25, 2018}}</ref> [[Anthony G. Brown]],<ref name=\"Backs\">{{cite news|last1=Fritze|first1=John|title=Anthony Brown backs David Trone in competitive House election|url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/news/maryland/politics/bs-md-brown-trone-20180306-story.html|accessdate=March 19, 2018|work=The Baltimore Sun|date=March 6, 2018}}</ref> and [[Doug Duncan]].<ref name=\"Notes\">{{cite news|last1=Baker|first1=Tamela|title=Political notes|url=https://www.heraldmailmedia.com/news/annapolis/political_notebook/political-notes/article_e07e4c5c-402b-5f97-a0f9-db9a0de29021.html|accessdate=March 19, 2018|work=The Herald-Mail|date=March 4, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn June 26, 2018, Trone won the Democratic primary election for Maryland's 6th district against seven challengers, with 40 percent of the vote.<ref name=pri18>{{cite web |url=http://elections.state.md.us/elections/2016/results/primary/gen_results_2016_3_00808.html |title=Official 2018 Gubernatorial Primary Election results for Representative in Congress: Congressional District 6 |date=July 31, 2018 |access-date=August 29, 2018 |publisher=Maryland State Board of Elections }}</ref><ref name=\"Schwartzman\">{{cite news |author1=Paul Schwartzman |author2=Jenna Portnoy |title=Trone wins Democratic primary for Delaney's House seat in Maryland |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/md-politics/trone-holds-early-lead-in-democratic-primary-for-delaneys-house-seat-in-maryland/2018/06/26/9c6354f2-77ac-11e8-80be-6d32e182a3bc_story.html |work=The Washington Post |date=June 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn the general election, Trone faced Republican Amie Hoeber and candidates from other parties.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gaines |first1=Danielle |title=Trone, Hoeber will meet at the general election in 6th District |url=https://www.fredericknewspost.com/news/continuing_coverage/election_2018/trone-hoeber-will-meet-at-the-general-election-in-th/article_70cae37e-4d0c-587e-af59-261b3a23ff12.html |work=The Frederick News-Post |date=June 26, 2018}}</ref> He received an endorsement from the ''Washington Post''.<ref>{{cite news |title=David Trone for Congress in Maryland |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/david-trone-for-congress-in-maryland/2018/10/22/6888a35c-d23e-11e8-8c22-fa2ef74bd6d6_story.html |work=The Washington Post |date=October 22, 2018}}</ref> On election day on November 6, 2018, Trone won the Congressional seat with 57.5 percent of the vote.<ref name=gen18>{{cite web |url=https://elections.maryland.gov/elections/2018/results/general/gen_results_2018_2_00806.html |title=Unofficial 2018 Gubernatorial General Election results for Representative in Congress: Congressional District 6 |date=November 8, 2018 |access-date=November 8, 2018 |publisher=Maryland State Board of Elections }}</ref><ref name=\"WTOP\">{{cite news |last1=Moore |first1=Jack |title=Maryland's 6th District: Democrat David Trone defeats GOP contender Amie Hoeber |url=https://wtop.com/maryland/2018/11/2018-election-results-maryland-congress-6th-district-david-trone-amie-hoeber/slide/1/ |work=WTOP |date=November 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.govtrack.us/congress/members/david_trone/412783|title=David Trone, Representative for Maryland's 6th Congressional District|website=GovTrack.us|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>===\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Education and Labor|Committee on Education and Labor]]'''\n**[[United States House Education Subcommittee on Higher Education and Workforce Investment|Subcommittee on Higher Education and Workforce Investment]] [[Subcommittee on Civil Rights and Human Services]]\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Foreign Affairs|Committee on Foreign Affairs]]'''\n**[[United States House Subcommittee on Europe, Eurasia, Energy, and the Environment|Subcommittee on Europe, Eurasia, Energy, and the Environment]]\n**[[United States House Foreign Affairs Subcommittee on the Middle East, North Africa and International Terrorism|Subcommittee on the Middle East, North Africa and International Terrorism]]\n*'''[[United States Congress Joint Economic Committee]]'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jec.senate.gov/public/index.cfm/democrats/democratic-members|title=Democratic Members - United States Joint Economic Committee|website=www.jec.senate.gov|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\n==Electoral history==\n{{Election box begin no change