entage = 38.0\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = Kevin Caldwell\n| party = Libertarian Party (United States)\n| votes = 4,972\n| percentage = 1.8\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = George Gluck\n| party = Green Party (United States)\n| votes = 3,275\n| percentage = 1.2\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = Write-ins\n| party = n/a\n| votes = 282\n| percentage = 0.1\n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n| votes = 277,084\n| percentage = 100.0\n}}\n{{Election box hold with party link without swing\n |winner    = Democratic Party (United States)\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n== Philanthropy ==\nIn addition to political contributions, Trone and his wife have supported a number of philanthropic efforts. They have been major contributors to the ACLU since 1994.<ref name=Peck/><ref name=\"Hsu\">{{cite news|last1=Hsu|first1=Spencer S.|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/public-safety/total-wine-co-founder-funds-15-million-aclu-push-to-aid-ex-convicts/2015/12/18/f046d036-a4f4-11e5-ad3f-991ce3374e23_story.html|title=Total Wine co-founder funding $15 million push to aid ex-convicts|accessdate=December 1, 2016|work=The Washington Post|date=December 21, 2015}}</ref> Their $15 million donation in 2015 supported the organization's efforts to promote criminal justice reform and improve employment opportunities for former [[prisoners]],<ref name=Turque/><ref name=Stolberg/><ref name=Hsu/> and established the Trone Center for Justice and Equality at the organization's national headquarters.<ref name=\"Root\">{{cite news|last1=Judge|first1=Monique|title=ACLU Makes the Case for Giving Formerly Incarcerated a Fair Chance at Employment|url=http://www.theroot.com/aclu-makes-the-case-for-giving-formerly-incarcerated-a-1795948983|accessdate=August 1, 2017|work=[[The Root (magazine)|The Root]]|publisher=[[Gizmodo Media Group]]|date=June 9, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=ACLU Announces New Trone Center for Criminal Justice Reform and Advisory Board of Private Sector and Education Leaders to Promote Reintegration|url=https://www.aclu.org/news/aclu-announces-new-trone-center-criminal-justice-reform-and-advisory-board-private-sector-and|publisher=[[American Civil Liberties Union]]|accessdate=August 1, 2017|date=December 21, 2016}}</ref> In 2016, the couple pledged $5 million to establish the Trone Family Public Policy Initiative Fund at their alma mater, the Wharton School of the University of Pennsylvania.<ref name=Wharton/><ref name=DiStefano/> \n\nIn mid 2017, the Trones donated $2.5 million to [[Bethesda, Maryland]]'s [[Suburban Hospital]] to support mental and behavioral health services and make improvements to the Old Georgetown Road campus. The couple's donation was inspired by their nephew's death from an opioid overdose in late 2016.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Zimmermann|first1=Joe|title=David Trone's Foundation Donates $2.5 Million to Suburban Hospital|journal=Bethesda|date=May 1, 2017|url=http://www.bethesdamagazine.com/Bethesda-Beat/2017/David-Trones-Foundation-Donates-25-Million-to-Suburban-Hospital/|accessdate=August 1, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"HighProfile\">{{cite news|last1=Turque|first1=Bill|title=David Trone stays high profile as he considers political future|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/md-politics/david-trone-stays-high-profile-as-he-considers-political-future/2017/06/15/a3344cca-5163-11e7-be25-3a519335381c_story.html|accessdate=August 1, 2017|work=The Washington Post|date=June 15, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Metcalf\">{{cite journal|last1=Metcalf|first1=Andrew|title=Trone Donates to Legal Fund to Assist Local Families Potentially Impacted by Trump's Proposed Travel Ban|journal=Bethesda|date=June 1, 2017|url=http://www.bethesdamagazine.com/Bethesda-Beat/2017/Trone-Donates-to-Legal-Fund-To-Assist-Local-Families-Potentially-Impacted-by-Trumps-Proposed-Travel-Ban/|accessdate=July 6, 2017}}</ref> The David and June Trone Family Foundation contributed $100,000 to the [[Catholic Legal Immigration Network]] in mid 2017 to support locals affected by Trump's travel ban, which the couple called \"outrageously egregious\". The Trones also donated to the ACLU's Montgomery County affiliate, the Latino immigrant organization CASA, and Interfaith Works.<ref name=Metcalf/><ref name=\"LegalAid\">{{cite news|last1=Turque|first1=Bill|title=Trone to fund legal aid for families who could be impacted by travel ban|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/md-politics/trone-to-fund-legal-aid-for-families-who-could-be-impacted-by-travel-ban/2017/06/01/9745caee-46ee-11e7-bcde-624ad94170ab_story.html|accessdate=August 1, 2017|work=The Washington Post|date=June 1, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Kazour\">{{cite news|last1=Kazour|first1=Mona|title=Legal Assistance for Montgomery County Families Affected by Trump Travel Ban|url=https://patch.com/maryland/bethesda-chevychase/legal-assistance-montgomery-county-families-affected-trump-travel-ban|accessdate=August 1, 2017|work=Bethesda Patch|date=June 2, 2017}}</ref>\n\nTrone's contributions to Furman University include a $5 million grant for a student center and to create men's and women's lacrosse teams, and the lead $500,000 gift for the Riley Foundation's endowment to support disadvantaged South Carolina students.<ref name=Felicien/><ref name=\"Dabbs\">{{cite web|last1=Dabbs|first1=Kate Hofler|first2=Evan|last2=Hildreth|title=Raising Up Riley: An Endowment for the Riley Institute|url=https://news.furman.edu/2012/12/01/raising-up-riley-an-endowment-for-the-riley-institute/|publisher=Furman University|accessdate=February 23, 2017|date=December 1, 2012}}</ref> The Trone Student Center was dedicated in 2013 and named for Trone and his wife, in honor of their $3.5 million contribution.<ref name=Furman/>\n\n== Personal life ==\nTrone serves as chair of the Trone Private Sector and Education Advisory Council at the ACLU Trone Center.<ref name=Hsu/><ref name=\"Leadership\">{{cite journal|title=Business Notes: Leadership Montgomery Announces 2018 Participants|journal=Bethesda|date=August 1, 2017|url=http://www.bethesdamagazine.com/Bethesda-Beat/2017/Business-Notes-Leadership-Montgomery-Announces-2018-Participants/|accessdate=July 6, 2017}}</ref> He has served on the [[Bullis School]]'s board of trustees since 2006.<ref>{{cite web|title=Trustees|url=http://www.bullis.org/page.cfm?p=963|publisher=[[Bullis School]]|accessdate=August 1, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170801200150/http://www.bullis.org/page.cfm?p=963|archive-date=August 1, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Kids Enjoy Exercise Now (KEEN) Greater DC gave Trone the \"Distinguished Service Award\" for his many contributions to the organization, which provides recreational programs for children with developmental and physical disabilities.<ref name=\"KEEN\">{{cite web|title=Annual Report 2012|url=http://www.keengreaterdc.org/sites/default/files/KEENGDC_Annual_Report_2012_Final.pdf|publisher=KEEN Greater DC|accessdate=December 21, 2016|format=PDF|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160127194447/http://www.keengreaterdc.org/sites/default/files/KEENGDC_Annual_Report_2012_Final.pdf|archive-date=January 27, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> He was honored at the 2014 [[Ernst & Young]] Entrepreneur of the Year Awards Greater Washington, in the \"large company\" category.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Koeppen|first1=Brynn|title=Ernst and Young Entrepreneur of the Year Awards Greater Washington Revealed: ECS Federal, Matchbox Among Winners|url=http://www.washingtonexec.com/2014/06/ernst-young-entrepreneur-year-awards-greater-washington-revealed-ecs-federal-matchbox-among-winners/|accessdate=December 21, 2016|work=WashingtonExec|date=June 20, 2014}}</ref> In 2015, Trone was invited by the [[American University]]'s Kennedy Political Union and the [[Kogod School of Business]] to speak to students and faculty about entrepreneurship and business leadership.<ref name=Rozen/> He was awarded the [[Anti-Defamation League]]'s annual achievement award in 2016.<ref name=\"Schere\">{{cite journal|last1=Schere|first1=Daniel|title=Did ADL endorse David Trone?|url=http://washingtonjewishweek.com/30718/did-adl-endorse-david-trone/featured-slider-post/|accessdate=December 21, 2016|work=[[Washington Jewish Week]]|date=April 20, 2016|issn=0746-9373}}</ref> In 2016, Trone joined the boards of [[American University]] and the Montgomery County Chamber of Commerce.<ref>American University: * {{cite web|title=Current Trustees|url=http://www.american.edu/trustees/Current-Trustees.cfm|publisher=[[American University]]|accessdate=February 23, 2017}} * {{cite web|title=Board of Trustees Late Fall 2016 Meeting Summary|url=http://www.american.edu/trustees/Announcement-November-30-2016.cfm|publisher=American University|accessdate=February 23, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Board of Directors|url=http://www.mcccmd.com/about-mccc/board-directory/board-directors|publisher=Montgomery County Chamber of Commerce|accessdate=February 23, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170801200139/http://www.mcccmd.com/about-mccc/board-directory/board-directors|archive-date=August 1, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Trone received Furman University's Carl F. Kohrt Distinguished Alumni Award, which is presented \"to an alumnus in recognition of significant professional or personal accomplishments and in gratitude for continued loyalty\".<ref name=\"Felicien\">{{cite news|last1=Felicien|first1=Tesalon|title=Total Wine and More's David Trone to receive distinguished Furman award|url=http://www.greenvilleonline.com/story/money/business/2017/02/21/total-wine-and-mores-david-trone-receive-distinguished-furman-award/98190412/|accessdate=February 23, 2017|work=[[The Greenville News]]|publisher=Gannett Company|location=Greenville, South Carolina}}</ref> He served on Furman University's board of trustees from 2010 to 2016.<ref name=Felicien/>\n\nDuring his 2018 campaign, Trone was diagnosed with cancer and underwent chemotherapy and surgery to remove a kidney; he was declared cancer-free by October.<ref name=\"cancer\">{{cite news |last1=Schwartzman |first1=Paul |title=David Trone says he is 'cancer free' three weeks after surgery |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/md-politics/trone-declares-himself-cancer-free-three-weeks-after-surgery/2018/10/02/3d694146-c680-11e8-b1ed-1d2d65b86d0c_story.html |work=The Washington Post |date=October 2, 2018}}</ref>\n\n{{as of|2016}}, the Trones live in [[Potomac, Maryland]].<ref name=Turque/><ref name=\"Spends\">{{cite news|last1=Turque|first1=Bill|title=David Trone spends $9.1 million of his own money on Md. congressional race|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/md-politics/david-trone-spends-91-million-of-his-own-money-on-md-congressional-race/2016/04/12/29f5827c-00c2-11e6-b823-707c79ce3504_story.html|accessdate=December 1, 2016|work=The Washington Post|date=April 12, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title=Total Wine co-owner will fund his run for Congress|journal=Washington Business Journal|date=January 28, 2016|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/washington/morning_call/2016/01/total-wine-coowner-will-fund-his-run-for-congress.html|accessdate=December 1, 2016|publisher=[[American City Business Journals]]}}</ref>\nTrone was raised Lutheran. His wife and all four children are Jewish and attend Temple Beth Ami in Rockville.<ref name=\"WJW\">{{cite journal|last1=Schere|first1=Dan|title=In race for Maryland's 6th, businessman Trone highlights opioid crisis|journal=Washington Jewish Week|date=February 21, 2018|url=http://washingtonjewishweek.com/44208/in-race-for-marylands-6th-businessman-trone-highlights-opioid-crisis/featured-slider-post/|accessdate=April 18, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Cortellessa\">{{cite news|last1=Cortellessa|first1=Eric|title=The Maryland wine mogul who is staking his fortune on reaching Capitol Hill|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/the-maryland-wine-mogul-who-is-staking-his-fortune-on-reaching-capitol-hill/|accessdate=May 25, 2018|work=[[The Times of Israel]]|date=March 24, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of people from Potomac, Maryland]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{Cite news|url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/news/opinion/oped/bs-ed-op-0615-opioid-home-20170612-story.html|first=David|last=Trone|title=The opioid crisis hits home for Maryland man|date=June 14, 2017|work=[[The Baltimore Sun]]}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://trone.house.gov/ Congressman David Trone] official U.S. House website\n*[https://www.davidtrone.com/ David Trone for Congress]\n{{CongLinks|votesmart=167336|congbio=T000483|fec=H6MD08549|congress=david-trone/T000483}}\n* {{Commons category-inline|David Trone}}\n* {{Cite journal|url=http://mydigitalpublication.com/publication/?i=394294#%7Bissue_id:394294,page:0%7D|title=The Art of Leadership|work=Montgomery Magazine|date=April\u2013May 2017}}\n* {{C-SPAN|David Trone}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[John Delaney (Maryland politician)|John Delaney]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[List of United States Representatives from Maryland|U.S. House of Representatives]]<br>from [[Maryland's 6th congressional district]]|years=2019\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-prec|usa}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Lori Trahan]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Seniority in the United States House of Representatives|United States Representatives by seniority]]|years=420th}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Lauren Underwood]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{MD-FedRep}}\n{{USHouseCurrent}}\n{{USCongRep-start|congresses= 116th [[United States Congress]] |state=[[Maryland]]}}\n{{USCongRep/MD/116}}\n{{USCongRep-end}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Trone, David}}\n[[Category:1950s births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:21st-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:American company founders]]\n[[Category:American philanthropists]]\n[[Category:American retail chief executives]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Maryland]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Furman University alumni]]\n[[Category:Kidney cancer survivors]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Maryland Democrats]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from Maryland]]\n[[Category:People from Adams County, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:People from Potomac, Maryland]]\n[[Category:Retail company founders]]\n[[Category:Wharton School of the University of Pennsylvania alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Cilidus", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCommittee assignments{{Cite web|url=https://www.govtrack.us/congress/members/david_trone/412783|title=David Trone, Representative for Maryland's 6th Congressional District|website=GovTrack.us|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/David_Trone"}
{"title_page": "Sunswick Creek", "text_new": "{{short description|Buried stream in Queens, New York}}\n{{coord|40|46|07|N|73|56|16|W|display=title}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n[[File:1873_Beers_Map_of_Astoria_and_Long_Island_City,_Queens,_New_York_-_Geographicus_-_LongIslandCity-beers-1873.jpg|thumb|1873 map of Long Island City. Sunswick Creek starts at the center of the image and drains into the East River, at left<!-- need to add highlighting to this image -->]]\n'''Sunswick Creek''' is a buried stream located in [[Astoria, Queens|Astoria]] and [[Long Island City]], in the northwestern portion of [[Queens]] in [[New York City]]. It originated to the north of [[Queensboro Bridge]] and [[Queens Plaza (Queens)|Queens Plaza]] in Long Island City, flowing north to the present-day site of the [[Socrates Sculpture Park]] in Astoria, and emptying into the [[East River]]. The creek was named for a term in the [[Algonquin language]] that likely means \"Woman Chief\" or \"Sachem\u2019s Wife.\" \n\nThe mouth of the creek was settled in the late 17th century by William Hallet, who built a [[milldam]] at the creek's mouth to create a mill pond. Due to industrialization in Long Island City, the creek became heavily polluted and was covered-over starting in the late 19th century.\n\n== Course ==\nPrior to its burial, Sunswick Creek's source was located close to 21st Street north of what is now the [[Queensboro Bridge]] and [[Queens Plaza (Queens)|Queens Plaza]], within the Long Island City subsection of Ravenswood. The creek passed north near the current site of the [[Queensbridge Houses]] and the [[Ravenswood Generating Station]], roughly following the present path of 21st Street.<ref name=\"Kadinsky2016\">{{Cite Hidden Waters NYC|pages=96-98}}</ref>{{rp|96}} A large city block, now the site of the [[Long Island City High School]], marks the former above-ground course of the creek. Sunswick Creek drained into the [[East River]] near the present [[Socrates Sculpture Park]] in [[Astoria, Queens|Astoria]].<ref name=\"Kadinsky2016\" />{{Rp|97}}\n\n== Etymology ==\nThe term \"Sunswick\" was a neighborhood name formerly applied to the surrounding portions of Ravenswood and Astoria. It is believed to have originated from a Native American language, possibly the [[Algonquin language|Algonquin]] word \"Sunkisq.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nycgovparks.org/parks/playground-thirty-five-xxxv/history|title=Playground Thirty Five XXXV Highlights|publisher=[[New York City Department of Parks and Recreation]]|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref> The [[Greater Astoria Historical Society]] defines the term as \"meaning perhaps 'Woman Chief' or 'Sachem\u2019s Wife.'\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.astorialic.org/topics/names_p.php|title=History Topics|date=February 8, 2007|website=Greater Astoria Historical Society|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070208042542/http://www.astorialic.org/topics/names_p.php|archive-date=February 8, 2007|access-date=March 10, 2020}}</ref> This name is shared by Sunswick 3535, a bar at the intersection of 35th Street and 35th Avenue.<ref name=\"Kadinsky2016\" />{{Rp|98}} Additionally, the present-day 22nd Street was formerly named Sunswick Street.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://forgotten-ny.com/2010/12/long-island-city-necrology/|title=Long Island City Street Necrology|last=Walsh|first=Kevin|date=December 28, 2010|website=Forgotten New York|access-date=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n\n=== 17th through 19th centuries ===\nIn 1664, the land on the northern shore of the creek's mouth was purchased by British settler William Hallet (or Hallett), who obtained the plot from two native chiefs named Shawestcont and Erramorhar.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite book|last=von Skal|first=G.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qPYTAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA84|title=Illustrated History of the Borough of Queens, New York City|publisher=F.T. Smiley Publishing Company|year=1908|isbn=|location=|page=|pages=|access-date=March 10, 2020}}</ref>{{Rp|84}} This peninsula, which jutted out onto [[Hell Gate]] to the northwest, was acquired in portions and was later renamed [[Hallet's Cove]].<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|84}}<ref name=\"Ross Pelletreau 1905 p.\">{{cite book|last=Ross|first=P.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Y4c-AAAAYAAJ|title=A History of Long Island: From Its Earliest Settlement to the Present Time|last2=Pelletreau|first2=W.S.|publisher=Lewis Publishing Company|year=1905|series=A History of Long Island: From Its Earliest Settlement to the Present Time|page=|access-date=March 10, 2020|issue=v. 2}}</ref>{{Rp|295}} Hallet subsequently built a lime [[kiln]] on the creek. Sunswick Creek formed a navigable waterway with [[Dutch Kills]], another stream to the south, making it easy for merchants to transport produce and goods along the creek.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|19}} A [[milldam]] was built at the mouth of the creek in 1679, creating a small mill pond.<ref name=\"feis7\">{{Cite book|last=The Louis Berger Group, Inc.|first=|url=https://www1.nyc.gov/assets/planning/download/pdf/applicants/env-review/dutch_kills/07_feis.pdf|title=Phase IA Cultural Resource Assessment|date=May 2008|website=|publisher=[[New York City Department of City Planning]]|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=|chapter=Chapter 7: Historic Resources|access-date=March 10, 2020|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>{{Rp|4}} Joseph Hallett and Jacob Blackwell built a mill on the creek's right bank, near its mouth, in 1753.<ref name=\"Ross Pelletreau 1905 p.\" />{{Rp|296}}\n\nBy the 1860s and 1870s, Sunswick Creek was heavily polluted due to increasing industrialization, a lack of proper sewerage, and the high population density of Long Island City and Astoria.<ref name=\"feis7\" />{{Rp|4}} The historian [[Vincent F. Seyfried]] wrote that disease around Sunswick Creek and Dutch Kills had become common by 1866, and that \"The damming of the Sunswick Creek cut off the flushing-out of the meadow lands and the salt water that used to ebb and flow became stagnant and slimy and filled with mosquitoes.\"<ref name=\"feis7\" />{{Rp|4}}<ref name=\"Seyfried 1984 p.\">{{cite book|last=Seyfried|first=Vincent F.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xskXPwAACAAJ|title=300 Years of Long Island City: 1630-1930|publisher=Edgian Press|year=1984|series=Queens community series|page=945|access-date=March 10, 2020}}</ref> After outbreaks of disease in 1871 and 1875, the marshes surrounding the creek were drained in 1879.<ref name=\"feis7\" />{{Rp|4}} In addition, Long Island City had started building a proper sewage system in the 1870s, which was still not complete by the time Long Island City became part of the [[City of Greater New York]] in 1898.<ref name=\"feis7\" />{{Rp|5}} The creek was partially diverted into one of the sewage system's brick tunnels at Broadway, which was completed around 1893.<ref name=\"Kadinsky2016\" />{{Rp|97}}\n\n=== 20th century ===\nSunswick Meadows, a lowland north of the present Queensboro Bridge, was infilled with the construction of the bridge in the 1900s and 1910s.<ref name=\"feis7\" />{{Rp|6}} This was accomplished partly by dumping dirt from the excavation of [[New York City Subway]] tunnels in [[Manhattan]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://bklyn.newspapers.com/clip/46488298/|title=Will Fill in Marshes|date=September 15, 1911|work=Brooklyn Daily Eagle|access-date=March 10, 2020|page=12|via=Brooklyn Public Library; newspapers.com {{open access}}}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46489839/|title=Queens Building Boom|date=June 22, 1912|work=The Chat|access-date=February 2, 2020|page=32|via=newspapers.com {{open access}}}}</ref> In addition, street cleaners tossed dry rubbish into the lowland to raise the grade of nearby streets.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46489209/|title=Dry Refuse for Street Fill|date=March 16, 1911|work=Brooklyn Daily Eagle|access-date=March 10, 2020|page=14|via=Brooklyn Public Library; newspapers.com {{open access}}}}</ref> \n\nIn 1915, residents of Ravenswood sent a letter to the [[New York City Board of Health]] to complain about the [[Tide gate|tide gates]] along Sunswick Creek, which had been installed to alleviate an infestation of mosquitoes. The residents claimed that the tide gates were actually keeping mosquitoes in the creek, since these gates resulted in stagnant water, and threatened to open the tide gates. In response, the Board of Health suggested filling up their land, which the ''Brooklyn Times-Union'' reported would require the infilling of {{Convert|6|acre||abbr=}} to a depth of {{Convert|8|to|10|ft|abbr=}}. The operation had a projected total cost of over $100,000 ({{Inflation|index=US|value=100000|start_year=1915|fmt=eq}}), which was not affordable for most of the neighborhood's residents.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46488791/|title=Health Board Order Defied|date=September 7, 1915|work=Brooklyn Times-Union|access-date=March 10, 2020|page=6|via=newspapers.com {{open access}}}}</ref> Early the next year, in April 1916, residents broke down the barriers with axes.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46489696/|title=Taxpayers Break Down Sunswick Creek Barrier|date=April 12, 1916|work=Brooklyn Standard Union|access-date=March 10, 2020|page=7|via=newspapers.com {{open access}}}}</ref> Afterward, the New York City health commissioner told a local newspaper that the residents \"prefer to live like hogs,\" prompting outrage from local residents.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46489618/|title=Demand Apology from Dr. Haven Emerson|date=April 15, 1916|work=Brooklyn Standard Union|access-date=March 10, 2020|page=5|via=newspapers.com {{open access}}}}</ref> Afterward, the Queens [[borough president]], [[Maurice E. Connolly]], announced a plan to install two tide gates on the creek.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://bklyn.newspapers.com/clip/46488429/|title=Connolly After Skeeters|date=May 24, 1916|work=Brooklyn Daily Eagle|access-date=March 10, 2020|page=12|via=Brooklyn Public Library; newspapers.com {{open access}}}}</ref> \n\nBy the end of 1916, the New York City government proposed to close up Sunswick Creek, mandating that households living nearby divert their sewage elsewhere.<ref>{{cite book|author=New York (N.Y.). Dept. of Health|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NAkgAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA41|title=Annual Report of the Department of Health of the City of New York|author2=New York (N.Y.). Board of Health|year=1916|page=41|access-date=March 10, 2020}}</ref> A 1920 ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'' article stated that the former path of the creek had been mostly developed with industrial buildings.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://bklyn.newspapers.com/clip/46489454/|title=Largest Movie Studios in the U.S. Planned for L.I. City|date=January 18, 1920|work=Brooklyn Daily Eagle|access-date=March 10, 2020|page=66|via=Brooklyn Public Library; newspapers.com {{open access}}}}</ref> During excavations for a sewer line at Vernon Boulevard and Broadway in 1957, construction workers found remnants of the former grist mill on the creek's mouth.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1957/04/20/archives/2-wheels-of-1829-mill-uncovered-in-queens.html|title=2 Wheels of 1829 Mill Uncovered in Queens|date=April 20, 1957|work=The New York Times|access-date=March 11, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n== Legacy ==\nThe creek now exists underground as part of a sewage tunnel, which was documented online by urban explorer Steven Duncan.<ref name=\"Kadinsky2016\" />{{Rp|97}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nationalgeographic.com/environment/photos/underground-rivers/|first=Brian Clark |last=Howard |title=11 Rivers Forced Underground|date=December 1, 2016|website=National Geographic|access-date=March 10, 2020}}</ref> According to one blogger, during heavy rains, the creek could be heard near the [[Sohmer and Company Piano Factory]], across from Socrates Sculpture Park.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.brownstoner.com/history/sunswick-creek-astoria-and-ravenswoods-forgotten-river/|title=Sunswick Creek, Astoria and Ravenswood\u2019s Forgotten River|last=Waxman|first=Mitch|date=February 26, 2015|website=Brownstoner|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 10, 2020}}</ref> In 2011 and 2012, the Socrates Sculpture Park and [[Noguchi Museum]] commissioned a work from artist [[Mary Miss]], entitled ''Ravenswood/CaLL'', which consisted of several signs and mirrors along the course of the creek.<ref name=\"Kadinsky2016\" />{{Rp|98}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://socratessculpturepark.org/artist/miss-mary/|title=Mary Miss|website=Socrates Sculpture Park|language=en|access-date=March 11, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nycgovparks.org/art/riversideparkfund.org/page18|title=Art in the Parks Current Exhibitions|publisher=[[New York City Department of Parks and Recreation]]|access-date=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{New York City waterways}}\n\n[[Category:Rivers of New York (state)]]\n[[Category:History of New York City]]\n[[Category:Long Island City]]\n[[Category:East River]]\n[[Category:Rivers of Queens, New York]]\n[[Category:Subterranean rivers of the United States]]\n[[Category:Astoria, Queens]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Buried stream in Queens, New York}}\n{{coord|40|46|07|N|73|56|16|W|display=title}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n[[File:1873_Beers_Map_of_Astoria_and_Long_Island_City,_Queens,_New_York_-_Geographicus_-_LongIslandCity-beers-1873.jpg|thumb|1873 map of Long Island City. Sunswick Creek starts at the center of the image and drains into the East River, at left<!-- need to add highlighting to this image -->]]\n'''Sunswick Creek''' is a buried stream located in [[Astoria, Queens|Astoria]] and [[Long Island City]], in the northwestern portion of [[Queens]] in [[New York City]]. It originated to the north of [[Queensboro Bridge]] and [[Queens Plaza (Queens)|Queens Plaza]] in Long Island City, flowing north to the present-day site of the [[Socrates Sculpture Park]] in Astoria, and emptying into the [[East River]]. The creek was named for a term in the [[Algonquin language]] that likely means \"Woman Chief\" or \"Sachem\u2019s Wife\". \n\nThe mouth of the creek was settled in the late 17th century by William Hallet, who built a [[milldam]] at the creek's mouth to create a mill pond. Due to industrialization in Long Island City, the creek became heavily polluted and was covered-over starting in the late 19th century.\n\n== Course ==\nPrior to its burial, Sunswick Creek's source was located close to 21st Street north of what is now the [[Queensboro Bridge]] and [[Queens Plaza (Queens)|Queens Plaza]], within the Long Island City subsection of Ravenswood. The creek passed north near the current site of the [[Queensbridge Houses]] and the [[Ravenswood Generating Station]], roughly following the present path of 21st Street.<ref name=\"Kadinsky2016\">{{Cite Hidden Waters NYC|pages=96-98}}</ref>{{rp|96}} A large city block, now the site of the [[Long Island City High School]], marks the former above-ground course of the creek. Sunswick Creek drained into the [[East River]] near the present [[Socrates Sculpture Park]] in [[Astoria, Queens|Astoria]].<ref name=\"Kadinsky2016\" />{{Rp|97}}\n\n== Etymology ==\nThe term \"Sunswick\" was a neighborhood name formerly applied to the surrounding portions of Ravenswood and Astoria. It is believed to have originated from a Native American language, possibly the [[Algonquin language|Algonquin]] word \"Sunkisq\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nycgovparks.org/parks/playground-thirty-five-xxxv/history|title=Playground Thirty Five XXXV Highlights|publisher=[[New York City Department of Parks and Recreation]]|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref> The [[Greater Astoria Historical Society]] defines the term as \"meaning perhaps 'Woman Chief' or 'Sachem\u2019s Wife'\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.astorialic.org/topics/names_p.php|title=History Topics|date=February 8, 2007|website=Greater Astoria Historical Society|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070208042542/http://www.astorialic.org/topics/names_p.php|archive-date=February 8, 2007|access-date=March 10, 2020}}</ref> This name is shared by Sunswick 3535, a bar at the intersection of 35th Street and 35th Avenue.<ref name=\"Kadinsky2016\" />{{Rp|98}} Additionally, the present-day 22nd Street was formerly named Sunswick Street.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://forgotten-ny.com/2010/12/long-island-city-necrology/|title=Long Island City Street Necrology|last=Walsh|first=Kevin|date=December 28, 2010|website=Forgotten New York|access-date=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n\n=== 17th through 19th centuries ===\nIn 1664, the land on the northern shore of the creek's mouth was purchased by British settler William Hallet (or Hallett), who obtained the plot from two native chiefs named Shawestcont and Erramorhar.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite book|last=von Skal|first=G.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qPYTAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA84|title=Illustrated History of the Borough of Queens, New York City|publisher=F.T. Smiley Publishing Company|year=1908|isbn=|location=|page=|pages=|access-date=March 10, 2020}}</ref>{{Rp|84}} This peninsula, which jutted out onto [[Hell Gate]] to the northwest, was acquired in portions and was later renamed [[Hallet's Cove]].<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|84}}<ref name=\"Ross Pelletreau 1905 p.\">{{cite book|last=Ross|first=P.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Y4c-AAAAYAAJ|title=A History of Long Island: From Its Earliest Settlement to the Present Time|last2=Pelletreau|first2=W.S.|publisher=Lewis Publishing Company|year=1905|series=A History of Long Island: From Its Earliest Settlement to the Present Time|page=|access-date=March 10, 2020|issue=v. 2}}</ref>{{Rp|295}} Hallet subsequently built a lime [[kiln]] on the creek. Sunswick Creek formed a navigable waterway with [[Dutch Kills]], another stream to the south, making it easy for merchants to transport produce and goods along the creek.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|19}} A [[milldam]] was built at the mouth of the creek in 1679, creating a small mill pond.<ref name=\"feis7\">{{Cite book|last=The Louis Berger Group, Inc.|first=|url=https://www1.nyc.gov/assets/planning/download/pdf/applicants/env-review/dutch_kills/07_feis.pdf|title=Phase IA Cultural Resource Assessment|date=May 2008|website=|publisher=[[New York City Department of City Planning]]|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=|chapter=Chapter 7: Historic Resources|access-date=March 10, 2020|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>{{Rp|4}} Joseph Hallett and Jacob Blackwell built a mill on the creek's right bank, near its mouth, in 1753.<ref name=\"Ross Pelletreau 1905 p.\" />{{Rp|296}}\n\nBy the 1860s and 1870s, Sunswick Creek was heavily polluted due to increasing industrialization, a lack of proper sewerage, and the high population density of Long Island City and Astoria.<ref name=\"feis7\" />{{Rp|4}} The historian [[Vincent F. Seyfried]] wrote that disease around Sunswick Creek and Dutch Kills had become common by 1866, and that \"The damming of the Sunswick Creek cut off the flushing-out of the meadow lands and the salt water that used to ebb and flow became stagnant and slimy and filled with mosquitoes.\"<ref name=\"feis7\" />{{Rp|4}}<ref name=\"Seyfried 1984 p.\">{{cite book|last=Seyfried|first=Vincent F.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xskXPwAACAAJ|title=300 Years of Long Island City: 1630-1930|publisher=Edgian Press|year=1984|series=Queens community series|page=945|access-date=March 10, 2020}}</ref> After outbreaks of disease in 1871 and 1875, the marshes surrounding the creek were drained in 1879.<ref name=\"feis7\" />{{Rp|4}} In addition, Long Island City had started building a proper sewage system in the 1870s, which was still not complete by the time Long Island City became part of the [[City of Greater New York]] in 1898.<ref name=\"feis7\" />{{Rp|5}} The creek was partially diverted into one of the sewage system's brick tunnels at Broadway, which was completed around 1893.<ref name=\"Kadinsky2016\" />{{Rp|97}}\n\n=== 20th century ===\nSunswick Meadows, a lowland north of the present Queensboro Bridge, was infilled with the construction of the bridge in the 1900s and 1910s.<ref name=\"feis7\" />{{Rp|6}} This was accomplished partly by dumping dirt from the excavation of [[New York City Subway]] tunnels in [[Manhattan]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://bklyn.newspapers.com/clip/46488298/|title=Will Fill in Marshes|date=September 15, 1911|work=Brooklyn Daily Eagle|access-date=March 10, 2020|page=12|via=Brooklyn Public Library; newspapers.com {{open access}}}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46489839/|title=Queens Building Boom|date=June 22, 1912|work=The Chat|access-date=February 2, 2020|page=32|via=newspapers.com {{open access}}}}</ref> In addition, street cleaners tossed dry rubbish into the lowland to raise the grade of nearby streets.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46489209/|title=Dry Refuse for Street Fill|date=March 16, 1911|work=Brooklyn Daily Eagle|access-date=March 10, 2020|page=14|via=Brooklyn Public Library; newspapers.com {{open access}}}}</ref> \n\nIn 1915, residents of Ravenswood sent a letter to the [[New York City Board of Health]] to complain about the [[Tide gate|tide gates]] along Sunswick Creek, which had been installed to alleviate an infestation of mosquitoes. The residents claimed that the tide gates were actually keeping mosquitoes in the creek, since these gates resulted in stagnant water, and threatened to open the tide gates. In response, the Board of Health suggested filling up their land, which the ''Brooklyn Times-Union'' reported would require the infilling of {{Convert|6|acre||abbr=}} to a depth of {{Convert|8|to|10|ft|abbr=}}. The operation had a projected total cost of over $100,000 ({{Inflation|index=US|value=100000|start_year=1915|fmt=eq}}), which was not affordable for most of the neighborhood's residents.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46488791/|title=Health Board Order Defied|date=September 7, 1915|work=Brooklyn Times-Union|access-date=March 10, 2020|page=6|via=newspapers.com {{open access}}}}</ref> Early the next year, in April 1916, residents broke down the barriers with axes.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46489696/|title=Taxpayers Break Down Sunswick Creek Barrier|date=April 12, 1916|work=Brooklyn Standard Union|access-date=March 10, 2020|page=7|via=newspapers.com {{open access}}}}</ref> Afterward, the New York City health commissioner told a local newspaper that the residents \"prefer to live like hogs\", prompting outrage from local residents.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46489618/|title=Demand Apology from Dr. Haven Emerson|date=April 15, 1916|work=Brooklyn Standard Union|access-date=March 10, 2020|page=5|via=newspapers.com {{open access}}}}</ref> Afterward, the Queens [[borough president]], [[Maurice E. Connolly]], announced a plan to install two tide gates on the creek.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://bklyn.newspapers.com/clip/46488429/|title=Connolly After Skeeters|date=May 24, 1916|work=Brooklyn Daily Eagle|access-date=March 10, 2020|page=12|via=Brooklyn Public Library; newspapers.com {{open access}}}}</ref> \n\nBy the end of 1916, the New York City government proposed to close up Sunswick Creek, mandating that households living nearby divert their sewage elsewhere.<ref>{{cite book|author=New York (N.Y.). Dept. of Health|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NAkgAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA41|title=Annual Report of the Department of Health of the City of New York|author2=New York (N.Y.). Board of Health|year=1916|page=41|access-date=March 10, 2020}}</ref> A 1920 ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'' article stated that the former path of the creek had been mostly developed with industrial buildings.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://bklyn.newspapers.com/clip/46489454/|title=Largest Movie Studios in the U.S. Planned for L.I. City|date=January 18, 1920|work=Brooklyn Daily Eagle|access-date=March 10, 2020|page=66|via=Brooklyn Public Library; newspapers.com {{open access}}}}</ref> During excavations for a sewer line at Vernon Boulevard and Broadway in 1957, construction workers found remnants of the former grist mill on the creek's mouth.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1957/04/20/archives/2-wheels-of-1829-mill-uncovered-in-queens.html|title=2 Wheels of 1829 Mill Uncovered in Queens|date=April 20, 1957|work=The New York Times|access-date=March 11, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n== Legacy ==\nThe creek now exists underground as part of a sewage tunnel, which was documented online by urban explorer Steven Duncan.<ref name=\"Kadinsky2016\" />{{Rp|97}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nationalgeographic.com/environment/photos/underground-rivers/|first=Brian Clark |last=Howard |title=11 Rivers Forced Underground|date=December 1, 2016|website=National Geographic|access-date=March 10, 2020}}</ref> According to one blogger, during heavy rains, the creek could be heard near the [[Sohmer and Company Piano Factory]], across from Socrates Sculpture Park.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.brownstoner.com/history/sunswick-creek-astoria-and-ravenswoods-forgotten-river/|title=Sunswick Creek, Astoria and Ravenswood\u2019s Forgotten River|last=Waxman|first=Mitch|date=February 26, 2015|website=Brownstoner|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 10, 2020}}</ref> In 2011 and 2012, the Socrates Sculpture Park and [[Noguchi Museum]] commissioned a work from artist [[Mary Miss]], entitled ''Ravenswood/CaLL'', which consisted of several signs and mirrors along the course of the creek.<ref name=\"Kadinsky2016\" />{{Rp|98}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://socratessculpturepark.org/artist/miss-mary/|title=Mary Miss|website=Socrates Sculpture Park|language=en|access-date=March 11, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nycgovparks.org/art/riversideparkfund.org/page18|title=Art in the Parks Current Exhibitions|publisher=[[New York City Department of Parks and Recreation]]|access-date=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{New York City waterways}}\n\n[[Category:Rivers of New York (state)]]\n[[Category:History of New York City]]\n[[Category:Long Island City]]\n[[Category:East River]]\n[[Category:Rivers of Queens, New York]]\n[[Category:Subterranean rivers of the United States]]\n[[Category:Astoria, Queens]]\n", "name_user": "Chialynn", "label": "safe", "comment": "Proofreading.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sunswick_Creek"}
{"title_page": "Wyon family", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n[[File:Wyon.gif|alt=Drawing of William Wyon|thumb|[[William Wyon]] (1795 \u2013 1851)]]\nThe '''Wyon family''' was an English family of traditional die-engravers and medallists, many of whom went on to work in prominent roles at the [[Royal Mint]] or as engravers in a family die business.<ref>{{cite web|title=J.S. & A.B. Wyon, Engravers, London, England|url=https://collections.museumvictoria.com.au/articles/2088|publisher=Museums Victoria Collections|accessdate=6 May 2017}}</ref> Starting from Peter George (II) Wyon who migrated to [[England]] from [[Cologne]], [[Germany]] many subsequent descendants of have made notable contribution to British [[numismatics]]. Over the course of the 19th-century two members of the family became Chief Engraver at the Royal Mint with many more involved in coin design.<ref>{{DNB|no-icon=1|prescript=|wstitle=Wyon, Thomas (1792-1817)}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Reverend Allan Gairdner Wyon|url=http://sculpture.gla.ac.uk/view/person.php?id=msib2_1208277616|publisher=sculpture.gla.ac.uk|accessdate=6 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n*Peter George (II) Wyon \n**George Wyon (d.1796)\n***[[Thomas Wyon the elder]] (1767\u20131830)\n****[[Thomas Wyon]] (1792\u20131817)\n****[[Benjamin Wyon]] (1802\u20131858)\n*****[[Alfred Benjamin Wyon]] (1837-1884)\n*****[[Joseph Shepherd Wyon]] (1836-1873)\n*****[[Allan Wyon]] (1843\u20131907) -M- Harriet Gairdner\n******[[Reverend Allan Gairdner Wyon]] (1882-1962)\n******[[Olive Wyon]] (1881\u20131966)\n******[[Allan G. Wyon]] 1882\u20131962) -M- Eileen May Trench\n*******1 Daughter\n****[[Edward William Wyon]] (1811\u20131885) -M- Elizabeth Smyth\n*****[[Edward Alexander Wyon]] (1842\u20131872)\n***[[William Wyon]] (1795\u20131851)\n****[[Leonard Charles Wyon]] (1826\u20131891)\n***[[Peter Wyon]] (1797\u20131822)\n***George Wyon (1771) -M- Elizabeth Phillips\n****James Wyon (1804\u20131868)\n*****George William Wyon (1836\u20131862)\n*****Henry Wyon (1834\u20131856)\n****John George Wyon (1806)\n*****Edward Wyon(1857-1906)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n[[Category:British families of German ancestry]]\n[[Category:Business families]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n[[File:Wyon.gif|alt=Drawing of William Wyon|thumb|[[William Wyon]] (1795 \u2013 1851)]]\nThe '''Wyon family''' was an English family of traditional die-engravers and medallists, many of whom went on to work in prominent roles at the [[Royal Mint]] or as engravers in a family die business.<ref>{{cite web|title=J.S. & A.B. Wyon, Engravers, London, England|url=https://collections.museumvictoria.com.au/articles/2088|publisher=Museums Victoria Collections|accessdate=6 May 2017}}</ref> Starting from Peter George (II) Wyon who migrated to [[England]] from [[Cologne]], [[Germany]] many subsequent descendants of have made notable contribution to British [[numismatics]]. Over the course of the 19th-century two members of the family became Chief Engraver at the Royal Mint with many more involved in coin design.<ref>{{DNB|no-icon=1|prescript=|wstitle=Wyon, Thomas (1792-1817)}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Reverend Allan Gairdner Wyon|url=http://sculpture.gla.ac.uk/view/person.php?id=msib2_1208277616|publisher=sculpture.gla.ac.uk|accessdate=6 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n*Peter George (II) Wyon \n**George Wyon (d.1796)\n***[[Thomas Wyon the elder]] (1767\u20131830)\n****[[Thomas Wyon]] (1792\u20131817)\n****[[Benjamin Wyon]] (1802\u20131858)\n*****[[Alfred Benjamin Wyon]](1837-1884)\n*****[[Joseph Shepherd Wyon]](1836-1873)\n****[[Edward William Wyon]](1811-1876)\n*****[[Allan Wyon]] (1843\u20131907) -M- Harriet Gairdner\n******[[Reverend Allan Gairdner Wyon]] (1882-1962)\n******[[Olive Wyon]] (1881\u20131966)\n******[[Allan G. Wyon]] 1882\u20131962) -M- Eileen May Trench\n*******1 Daughter\n****[[Edward William Wyon]] (1811\u20131885) -M- Elizabeth Smyth\n*****[[Edward Alexander Wyon]](1842\u20131872)\n***[[William Wyon]] (1795\u